⚖️ CS-24-01 | Abhimeet Sinha & Ors. v. High Court of Judicature at Patna & Ors. (2024)
Bench: Justices Hrishikesh Roy and Prashant Kumar Mishra
 Date of Judgment: 6 May 2024
 Constitutional Provisions: Articles 14, 16 and 21 of the Constitution of India

🧩 Facts of the Case
Several candidates who did not clear the Bihar Judicial Service Examination questioned the rule that fixed minimum qualifying marks in the oral interview (viva voce). They argued that it distorted fair competition—those scoring high in the written exam could still be rejected if they did not reach the oral threshold. This, they claimed, violated the equality guarantee under Articles 14 and 16 and contradicted the approach taken in All India Judges’ Association (1992) and the Shetty Commission recommendations, which had advised avoiding minimum interview marks.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
1️⃣ Whether prescribing minimum qualifying marks for the viva voce stage in judicial service recruitment contradicts the law declared in All India Judges’ Association v. Union of India (1992).
 2️⃣ Whether such a prescription amounts to arbitrariness and violates Articles 14 and 16 of the Constitution.

🧠 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court upheld the validity of the rule prescribing minimum viva voce marks.
 It held that setting a benchmark for interviews is constitutionally permissible so long as it is applied fairly and transparently. The Shetty Commission’s observations were recommendatory, not binding.
Ratio: Fixing reasonable qualifying marks in the interview stage is compatible with the equality clause if the criteria are objective, uniform, and aim at maintaining judicial competence.

💬 Reasoning of the Court
The All India Judges’ Association case never barred the use of qualifying marks; it only warned against excessive subjectivity.


Under Articles 233–235, High Courts possess administrative control over subordinate-judiciary recruitment.


The rule ensured standardization, transparency, and merit-based selection, which are consistent with constitutional fairness.


The threshold did not appear irrational or disproportionate to the purpose of selecting capable judges.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The petitions were dismissed. The Court held that the rule prescribing minimum interview marks for Bihar and Gujarat judicial recruitment was neither arbitrary nor violative of equality, and fell within the High Courts’ constitutional authority.

🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Reinforces High Court autonomy in judicial service administration under Articles 233–235.


Distinguishes between eligibility (objective) and suitability (subjective) criteria in selection.


Clarifies that advisory commission reports do not override properly framed rules.


Strengthens the principle that fair + uniform = constitutional when evaluating recruitment policies.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
1️⃣ 🧱 All India Judges’ Association v. Union of India (1992) 1 SCC 119
Held: Judicial officers’ pay and recruitment standards should be improved per the Shetty Commission.


Significance: Laid the groundwork for reforming judicial service conditions and emphasized fairness in recruitment.


2️⃣ ⚖️ Syed T.A. Naqshbandi v. State of Jammu & Kashmir (2003) 9 SCC 592
Held: High Courts have primacy in appointments and promotions of the subordinate judiciary.


Significance: Reinforced the constitutional independence of High Courts under Articles 233–235 and limited executive interference.


3️⃣ 🏛️ Kavita Kamboj v. High Court of Punjab & Haryana (2023) SCC OnLine SC 1249
Held: Transparency and fairness are essential in judicial service recruitment processes.


Significance: Clarified that interview evaluation methods must withstand Article 14 scrutiny and maintain merit-based selection.



⚖️ CS-24-02 | Abhishek Banerjee & Anr. v. Directorate of Enforcement (2024)
Bench: Justices Bela M. Trivedi and Satish Chandra Sharma
 Date of Judgment: 9 September 2024
 Provisions Involved:
Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 – Sections 190(1)(a) read with 200


Indian Penal Code, 1860 – Sections 120-B, 409 and 174


Prevention of Money Laundering Act, 2002 – Section 50 and related provisions


Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988 – Section 13(2) read with 13(1)(a)



🧩 Facts of the Case
Abhishek Banerjee, a Member of Parliament, and his wife Rujira Banerjee were summoned by the Enforcement Directorate (ED) under Section 50 of the PMLA in a money-laundering investigation linked to an alleged coal scam. They challenged the summons before the Supreme Court, contending that the ED lacked jurisdiction to compel them to appear in New Delhi rather than their residential jurisdiction of Kolkata. They argued that the ED must follow the procedural safeguards under the Code of Criminal Procedure and that the PMLA does not expressly override those provisions.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
1️⃣ Whether the ED can summon persons under Section 50 of the PMLA to appear outside their residential jurisdiction.
 2️⃣ Whether the CrPC applies to proceedings under the PMLA in the absence of specific procedure in the Act.
 3️⃣ Whether the ED’s powers under Section 50 infringe the constitutional rights to life and personal liberty under Article 21.

🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court dismissed the petition and upheld the ED’s authority to issue summons under Section 50 of the PMLA irrespective of territorial boundaries. It held that the PMLA is a special, self-contained law whose provisions override the CrPC whenever inconsistencies arise. Section 71 of the PMLA expressly gives it an overriding effect. The Court reiterated that the power to summon for inquiry under Section 50 does not violate fundamental rights, as such summons do not amount to compulsion to incriminate oneself.
Ratio: The PMLA being a special enactment prevails over the CrPC, and the ED may summon any person for inquiry at any place connected to the investigation so long as nexus exists with the alleged offence.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
The Court relied on the principle that special laws override general laws to resolve conflicts between PMLA and CrPC.


Section 50 of PMLA creates an independent mechanism for enforcement and investigation, distinct from the police investigation process under Chapter XII of CrPC.


The Court found sufficient territorial connection between Delhi and the alleged financial transactions to justify the ED’s jurisdiction.


Article 20(3) (protection against self-incrimination) was held inapplicable since the summons were part of an inquiry, not a criminal trial.


The Court stressed that procedural compliance under the PMLA is a statutory requirement, and its officers are bound by the Act rather than the CrPC.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The appeal was dismissed. The ED’s summons were held to be valid, non-arbitrary, and within the scope of its statutory powers. The Court affirmed that PMLA procedures take precedence over CrPC wherever they conflict.

🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Clarifies that PMLA procedures override CrPC in cases of overlap or inconsistency.


Reinforces the concept of PMLA as a self-contained code with independent investigative authority.


Narrows the scope of territorial jurisdiction challenges to ED summons.


Emphasizes that Article 20(3) rights do not apply at the summons stage.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
1️⃣ Vijay Madanlal Choudhary v. Union of India (2022)
Held: PMLA is a complete and self-contained code with its own procedures that override CrPC provisions where inconsistent.


Significance: Provided the legal foundation for the Court’s view that ED summons under Section 50 are not subject to CrPC’s territorial limits or investigation norms.


2️⃣ Tofan Singh v. State of Tamil Nadu (2020)
Held: Statements made to officers under certain special statutes may be inadmissible if they amount to confessional statements to police.


Significance: Helped distinguish the nature of ED officers under PMLA from ordinary police officers, justifying the Court’s finding that Section 50 inquiries are not criminal investigations.


3️⃣ Nikesh Tarachand Shah v. Union of India (2018)
Held: Earlier bail provisions of PMLA violated Articles 14 and 21 but were later rectified by amendment.


Significance: Reinforces the Court’s view that constitutional rights must coexist with PMLA’s stringent framework without diluting its special status.
