⚖️ CS-24-03 | Achin Gupta v. State of Haryana & Ors. (2024)
Bench: Justices J.B. Pardiwala & Manoj Misra
 Date of Judgment: 3 May 2024
 Key Statutes / Provisions:
Indian Penal Code, 1860 –


Section 323: Punishment for voluntarily causing hurt


Section 406: Criminal breach of trust


Section 498A: Cruelty by husband or relatives of husband


Section 506: Criminal intimidation


Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 – Section 482 (inherent powers of the High Court to prevent abuse of process)


Constitution of India – Articles 14 and 21 (right to equality and personal liberty)



🧩 Facts of the Case
The appellant, Achin Gupta, married the complainant in 2008. In 2019, Gupta filed for divorce, and in 2020, his mother lodged a domestic-violence complaint. Two years later, in April 2021, the complainant filed an FIR under Sections 323, 406, 498A, and 506 of the IPC alleging dowry harassment, physical abuse, and threats. The appellant contended that the FIR was retaliatory and vague, filed as a counter-blast to his divorce proceedings. The Punjab & Haryana High Court declined to quash the FIR under Section 482 CrPC, prompting the appeal to the Supreme Court.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
1️⃣ Whether the High Court erred in refusing to exercise its inherent power under Section 482 CrPC to quash the proceedings.
 2️⃣ Whether the FIR disclosed specific, cognizable offences or was a misuse of the criminal process arising out of matrimonial discord.
 3️⃣ Whether continuation of such proceedings amounted to harassment and abuse of process.

🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court allowed the appeal and quashed the criminal proceedings. It held that the FIR contained generalised and omnibus allegations without particular details of cruelty or demand. Such sweeping statements, without supporting material, warranted intervention under Section 482 CrPC.
Ratio: Courts must carefully examine matrimonial complaints under Section 498A and related offences to ensure that the criminal process is not used as a weapon of retaliation or coercion.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
The Court observed that the complaint was lodged two years after divorce proceedings began, which raised serious doubts about its bona fides.


No specific acts, dates, or instances of cruelty or breach of trust were cited, showing absence of prima facie evidence.


Relying on Bhajan Lal and Preeti Gupta, the Court reiterated that vague allegations and delay may justify quashing.


It cautioned that unverified allegations under Section 498A IPC often result in undue harassment and social stigma.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The Supreme Court quashed FIR No. 95 of 2021 and all related criminal proceedings, holding them to be an abuse of process. It also directed that a copy of the judgment be sent to the Ministry of Home Affairs and the Ministry of Law for consideration of appropriate legislative reforms to curb misuse of Section 498A IPC.

🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Reinforces judicial power under Section 482 CrPC to prevent misuse of criminal law.


Recognises increasing misuse of Section 498A in matrimonial conflicts and calls for legislative review.


Stresses that specific, credible allegations are essential before initiating prosecution.


Balances protection of women with safeguards against false or vindictive litigation.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
1️⃣ State of Haryana v. Bhajan Lal (1992)
Held: Listed illustrative categories where FIRs may be quashed if they lack substance or indicate mala fide intent
No offence disclosed: Where the allegations made in the FIR or complaint, even if taken at face value and accepted in their entirety, do not constitute any offence or make out a case against the accused.
Absence of cognizable offence: Where the allegations do not disclose a cognizable offence, justifying investigation by police under Section 156(1) CrPC.
Uncontroverted allegations and evidence fail to prove offence: Where the uncontroverted allegations and the evidence collected in support do not disclose the commission of any offence.
Allegations absurd or inherently improbable: Where the allegations in the FIR are so absurd and inherently improbable that no prudent person could ever reach a conclusion that there is sufficient ground for proceeding.
Lack of legal bar ignored: Where there exists an express legal bar in the Code or in any other law to the institution or continuance of proceedings (for example, prior sanction requirements).
Malicious or mala fide proceedings: Where the proceedings are manifestly attended with mala fide and/or instituted maliciously with an ulterior motive for wreaking vengeance on the accused.
Civil dispute cloaked as criminal case: Where the dispute is predominantly civil or contractual in nature, but has been given a criminal colour merely to exert pressure or settle personal scores.
Significance: These categories serve as guiding principles (not exhaustive) for the exercise of the High Court’s inherent power under Section 482 CrPC to prevent abuse of process of law and to secure the ends of justice — a doctrine reaffirmed repeatedly in cases like Achin Gupta v. State of Haryana (2024) and Neeharika Infrastructure (2021).


2️⃣ Preeti Gupta v. State of Jharkhand (2010)
Held: Courts must be cautious of exaggerated allegations in matrimonial cases under Section 498A.


Significance: Warned against mechanical prosecution in family disputes.


3️⃣ Arnesh Kumar v. State of Bihar (2014)
Held: Issued guidelines for arrest under Section 498A to prevent unnecessary detention.


Significance: Reinforced judicial safeguards against misuse of dowry-harassment provisions.



⚖️ CS-24-04 | Association for Democratic Reforms & Anr. v. Union of India & Ors. (2024)
Bench: Five-Judge Constitution Bench of the Supreme Court of India, led by Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud
 Date of Judgment: 15 February 2024
 Key Constitutional Provisions: Articles 19(1)(a) (Freedom of speech and expression) & 21 (Right to life and personal liberty)
 Key Statutory Scheme: Electoral Bonds Scheme, 2018

🧩 Facts of the Case
The petitioners, including the NGO Association for Democratic Reforms (ADR), challenged the validity of the Electoral Bonds Scheme introduced by the Government of India in 2018. Under this scheme, individuals and corporations could purchase bonds anonymously and donate them to political parties, with donor identity not disclosed publicly. The petitioners argued the scheme violated the voters’ right to information and democratic accountability, as it concealed the source of political funding and potentially enabled undue influence.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
Whether the Electoral Bonds Scheme violated the voters’ right to information under Article 19(1)(a).


Whether the anonymity of political donations under the scheme undermined the democratic process and equality of citizens under Article 14.


Whether the scheme’s objectives—such as curbing black money—justified the restrictions on donor transparency and disclosure.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court struck down the Electoral Bonds Scheme as unconstitutional. The Court held that the scheme’s anonymity feature deprived citizens of crucial information about political funding, thereby impinging their right to free speech and meaningful participation in elections. The scheme failed to meet the test of proportionality because the restriction on donor identity disclosure was neither justifiable nor the least restrictive means.
Ratio: A law regulating political funding must preserve transparency and enable voters to make informed choices — anonymous donations that obscure funding sources violate Article 19(1)(a) and undermine democratic fairness.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
The Court held that free speech includes the right to receive information, especially when funding of political parties impacts electoral choices.


The anonymity of donations thwarted visibility into how money flows to parties, thereby diluting accountability and public trust in electoral democracy.


The scheme set up an “unequal playing field” favouring entities that could give without attribution, raising concerns under Article 14 about equality in political participation.


While curbing black money was a legitimate state aim, the means adopted (anonymous bonds) were disproportionate to that aim and lacked proper safeguards of transparency.


The Court emphasised that disclosure must be mandated where public interest demands it; democratic integrity outweighs donor privacy in the context of political party funding.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The scheme was declared unconstitutional and struck down. The Court directed the government to frame a new legislative scheme regulating political funding that ensures disclosure, transparency and accountability consistent with constitutional mandates.

🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Marks a major victory for political transparency and the right to information in electoral law.


Underlines that restrictions on disclosure of political donations must pass the proportionality test under Articles 14 & 19.


Affirms that democracy demands not only formal rights but meaningful access to information for citizens to exercise those rights.


Signals that the legislature must design political funding laws with checks against invisible influence and hidden money in politics.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
Union of India v. Association for Democratic Reforms (2002) 5 SCC 294 – Held that political parties must disclose details of donations and expenditures, thereby establishing the right of voters to access such information.


Significance: Laid the foundation for transparency in electoral funding and informed the 2024 judgment’s approach to disclosure.


Khempal Singh v. State of Rajasthan (noted for the principle of proportionality in democratic context) – Affirmed that laws affecting political processes must be proportionate and justified.


Significance: Provided the analytical framework for assessing the scheme’s compatibility with Articles 14 & 19.

⚖️ CS-24-05 | Aligarh Muslim University through its Registrar (Faizan Mustafa) v. Naresh Agarwal & Ors. (2024)
Citation: (2024) INSC 856 | C.A. No. 2286 of 2006
 Bench: Chief Justice Dr. D.Y. Chandrachud, and Justices Sanjiv Khanna, Surya Kant, J.B. Pardiwala, Dipankar Datta, Manoj Misra, Satish Chandra Sharma
 Judgment Date: 8 November 2024
 Bench Strength: Seven-Judge Constitution Bench
 Majority: 4 : 3
 Key Provisions: Article 30(1) of the Constitution (Minority educational rights)
 Statute Involved: Aligarh Muslim University Act, 1920 and its Amendments (1951, 1965, 1981)

🧩 Factual Background
Origins: Sir Syed Ahmed Khan established the Mohammedan Anglo-Oriental College in 1877 to promote modern education among Indian Muslims. In 1920, the British Imperial Legislative Council enacted the Aligarh Muslim University Act, converting the college into a statutory university.


Post-Constitution: After 1950, Article 30(1) guaranteed minorities the right to “establish and administer” educational institutions.


In S. Azeez Basha v. Union of India (1968)*, the Supreme Court held that since AMU was “established by Parliament”, it was not a minority institution.


In 1981, Parliament amended the AMU Act, stating that the university was “an institution established by the Muslims of India”.


In 2005, the Allahabad High Court struck down AMU’s 50 % Muslim reservation in postgraduate medical courses, reaffirming Azeez Basha.


In 2019, a three-judge bench led by CJI Ranjan Gogoi referred the question of Azeez Basha’s correctness to a seven-judge Constitution Bench.



⚙️ Issues Before the Court
1️⃣ Whether Azeez Basha v. Union of India (1968) correctly held that AMU was not a minority educational institution.
 2️⃣ Whether an educational institution established by statute can qualify as a “minority institution” under Article 30(1).
 3️⃣ What are the criteria for determining when an institution qualifies as a minority educational institution.

🏛 Decision / Ratio Decidendi
By a 4:3 majority, the Supreme Court overruled Azeez Basha.


It held that an institution does not lose its minority character merely because it is incorporated or recognised by statute.


The right under Article 30(1) extends to institutions established both before and after 1950, if they were founded by and for a minority community.


“Establishment” refers to the founding initiative and community effort, while “incorporation” gives legal personality. The minority’s authorship and purpose remain decisive.


The Court clarified that AMU’s minority status would be determined separately by a regular bench based on factual evaluation under the new criteria.


Ratio: The test of minority status under Article 30(1) depends on who conceived, funded, and developed the institution, not on the formal mode of its legal incorporation.

💡 Reasons for the Decision
(a) Reference Validity
The majority upheld the Rahmaniya (1981) reference questioning Azeez Basha, holding that the Chief Justice, as master of the roster, has administrative discretion to assign a matter to a larger bench.


The dissent (Justices Kant, Datta, Sharma) argued that the two-judge bench in Rahmaniya lacked authority to doubt a five-judge precedent and to suggest a bench size.


(b) Establishment vs. Incorporation
The majority emphasised that “establishment” = founding initiative, “incorporation” = legal recognition.


If an institution had an independent existence before the statute, statutory incorporation cannot erase its minority character.


(c) Minority Rights and Article 30(1)
Minority rights under Article 30 are foundational, not derivative. They exist to protect cultural and educational identity, and cannot be limited by legislative formalities.


Article 30(1) also covers pre-Constitution institutions founded by minorities.


(d) Criteria for Determining Minority Educational Status
1️⃣ Who founded the institution: Was the initiative taken by a minority group?
 2️⃣ Purpose of establishment: Was the object to advance the minority’s educational/cultural interests?
 3️⃣ Source of funding and development: Did the minority community contribute to its creation (land, funds, infrastructure)?
 4️⃣ Control and administration: Is the governance structure consistent with minority aims (though full control is not mandatory)?
 5️⃣ Beneficiaries: The institution must primarily, though not exclusively, serve the minority community.
 6️⃣ Historical context: The status is judged as on the date the Constitution came into force.

🧭 Dissenting Views
Justice Surya Kant – The Rahmaniya reference was procedurally invalid; a Division Bench could not reopen a Constitution Bench ruling.


Justice Dipankar Datta – Azeez Basha was correctly decided; AMU’s creation by statute and state control meant it was not a minority institution.


Justice Satish C. Sharma – Minority status requires factual and legal control by the minority; statutory and financial control by the State negates it.



✅ Outcome
Azeez Basha (1968) was overruled.


The Court laid down binding criteria for determining minority educational status.


It remitted AMU’s specific minority claim to a regular bench for determination under the clarified framework.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Restores and expands the constitutional scope of Article 30(1) — protecting minority institutions irrespective of statutory incorporation.


Distinguishes founding intent from legislative recognition, ensuring minority rights survive statutory formalisation.


Balances minority autonomy with state oversight: regulation permissible, but essence of minority control must remain.


Strengthens the pluralist and secular character of Indian education policy by affirming cultural diversity through education.


Sets a new national benchmark for determining minority educational status across India.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
1️⃣ S. Azeez Basha v. Union of India (1968)
 Held: AMU was not a minority institution as it was created by statute.
 Overruled: 2024 judgment rejected this formalistic approach and restored substance over form.
2️⃣ Anjuman-e-Rahmaniya v. District Inspector of Schools (1981)
 Held: Questioned Azeez Basha’s correctness and referred the issue to a larger bench.
 Significance: Validated as a legitimate reference by the 2024 majority.
3️⃣ T.M.A. Pai Foundation v. State of Karnataka (2002)
 Held: Defined minority rights to establish and administer educational institutions.
 Significance: Provided interpretive framework for Article 30 autonomy.
4️⃣ P.A. Inamdar v. State of Maharashtra (2005)
 Held: Clarified limits on state regulation of minority and non-minority institutions.
 Significance: Balanced autonomy with regulatory fairness.
5️⃣ The Durgah Committee, Ajmer v. Syed Hussain Ali (1961)
 Held: Defined rights of religious denominations under Article 26.
 Significance: Cited (and distinguished) — the 2024 Court clarified that Article 26 and Article 30 confer distinct rights.

⚖️ CS-24-06 | Amutha v. A.R. Subramanian (2024)
Bench: Justices Vikram Nath & Prasanna B. Varale
 Date of Judgment: 19 December 2024
 Key Statutes / Provisions:
Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 – Sections 13(1)(ia) (cruelty) & 13(1)(ib) (desertion)


Code of Civil Procedure, 1908 – Section 100 (second appeal jurisdiction)


Constitution of India – Article 142 (complete justice)



🧩 Facts of the Case
The parties married in June 2002; both were software engineers. After childbirth in 2003, the wife returned to her parental home and subsequently refused to resume co-habitation. A protracted separation followed (over 15 years), during which the wife is alleged to have filed a false criminal complaint of dowry harassment against the husband and his family, but did not pursue it. The husband initiated divorce proceedings in 2010 on grounds of cruelty and desertion. The trial court and first appellate court denied the relief; the High Court reversed the decision granting divorce. The wife appealed to the Supreme Court.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
Whether the filing of false criminal complaints against a spouse amounts to mental cruelty under Section 13(1)(ia).


Whether prolonged separation—without reasonable cause or intention to reconcile—constitutes desertion under Section 13(1)(ib).


Whether the Court can recognise the ground of irretrievable breakdown of marriage (not explicitly in the Act) via its equitable jurisdiction under Article 142.


Whether the High Court exceeded its jurisdiction under Section 100 CPC by re-evaluating facts already adjudicated.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court upheld the High Court’s grant of divorce: the wife’s conduct (including the filing of a bogus criminal complaint and prolonged separation) was held to constitute mental cruelty; her extended non-cohabitation signified desertion; and the marriage had irretrievably broken down, making its continuation futile.
Ratio: A marriage may be dissolved when one spouse inflicts mental cruelty (including via false criminal litigation), or wilfully abandons the matrimonial home over a sustained period, and when reconciliation is impossible such that continuation serves no purpose.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
The Court observed that the wife’s false complaint caused mental anguish, anxiety and loss of reputation, thereby amounting to mental cruelty.


It held that separation of over 15 years, without any realistic effort at reunion, supported the inference of desertion.


The Court acknowledged that, though irretrievable breakdown is not a statutory ground, under Article 142 it may apply where marriage is a “dead relationship” and continuing it would be against justice.


On the Section 100 CPC point: The Court found the High Court had identified substantial questions of law and was justified in reversing earlier findings.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The appeal by the wife was dismissed; the decree of divorce in favour of the husband was affirmed. The Court also awarded lump-sum alimony and maintenance (despite the wife’s financial independence) in view of long separation and the interests of the child.

🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Reinforces that false criminal complaints against a spouse can amount to mental cruelty, justifying divorce.


Affirms that prolonged separation with no sincere reconciliation efforts can be treated as desertion and indicate irretrievable breakdown.


Signals willingness of the Court to invoke equitable jurisdiction (under Article 142) to dissolve marriages where statutory grounds are exhausted but reality demands closure.


Provides clarity on alimony even where maintenance was not claimed, emphasising equity and dignity post-marriage.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
Samar Ghosh v. Jaya Ghosh (2007) – Established rich criteria for mental cruelty (sustained conduct, emotional torment, disregard of duty).


Significance: The Court relied on this case to evaluate the wife’s conduct in Amutha.


Naveen Kohli v. Neelu Kohli (2006) – Recognised that long, voluntary separation may lead to irretrievable breakdown and divorce under Article 142.


Significance: Amutha re-emphasised this principle in the context of matrimonial relief.


K. Srinivas Rao v. D. A. Deepa (2013) – Held that filing of false criminal cases can amount to mental cruelty.


Significance: Directly relevant to the finding of cruelty in Amutha.



⚖️ CS-24-07 | Anees v. The State Govt. of NCT (2024)
Bench: Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud, Justice J.B. Pardiwala, and Justice Manoj Misra
 Date of Judgment: 3 May 2024
 Citation: 2024 INSC 368
 Key Statutes / Provisions:
Indian Penal Code, 1860: Section 302 – Murder


Indian Evidence Act, 1872: Section 106 – Burden of proof regarding facts within special knowledge



🧩 Facts of the Case
The appellant, Anees, was accused of murdering his wife, Saira, inside their home in Delhi. Only Anees, Saira, and their minor daughter were present at the time of death. The prosecution relied mainly on circumstantial evidence, including the appellant’s presence at the scene, recovery of the weapon, and forensic reports linking the blood samples to the deceased. Anees denied involvement, claiming his wife died by suicide.
 The trial court convicted him under Section 302 IPC, sentencing him to life imprisonment. The conviction was upheld by the High Court. Anees appealed to the Supreme Court, questioning the reliance on circumstantial evidence and the application of Section 106 of the Evidence Act.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
1️⃣ Whether the conviction for murder based solely on circumstantial evidence was sustainable.
 2️⃣ Whether the prosecution could rely on Section 106 of the Evidence Act to shift the burden of proof to the accused.
 3️⃣ Whether the courts below had ensured fair trial standards, particularly in handling hostile witnesses.

🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court dismissed the appeal and upheld the conviction under Section 302 IPC.
Ratio: Section 106 of the Evidence Act applies when the facts are within the exclusive knowledge of the accused and the prosecution has already established a complete chain of circumstances pointing to guilt. It cannot be used to fill gaps in the prosecution’s case.
The Court held that, given the offence occurred inside the matrimonial home and the accused offered no plausible explanation, the burden of proof under Section 106 legitimately shifted to him.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
The Court reaffirmed that the burden of proof always begins with the prosecution; Section 106 comes into play only after the prosecution has made a prima facie case.


The facts — the death occurring inside the home, inconsistent statements by the accused, and the absence of any alternate explanation — supported guilt.


The forensic evidence corroborated the prosecution’s theory, and the accused’s silence strengthened the inference of guilt.


The Court clarified that misuse of Section 106 (to substitute for weak investigation) is impermissible, but when the accused is in exclusive possession of the facts, his silence can legitimately strengthen the prosecution’s case.


The Court reiterated that trial judges must remain alert when witnesses turn hostile, especially minors, ensuring that truth is not suppressed.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The appeal was dismissed.


The conviction of Anees under Section 302 IPC and sentence of life imprisonment were upheld.


The Supreme Court underscored that the proper application of Section 106 strengthens, rather than replaces, the prosecution’s burden of proof.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Clarifies the limited but critical use of Section 106 Evidence Act — to explain facts within the accused’s knowledge once a complete chain of circumstances is proved.


Reiterates that circumstantial evidence can validly sustain conviction if it excludes every hypothesis other than guilt.


Strengthens judicial vigilance in trials involving hostile witnesses and intra-house crimes (“closed-room” cases).


Reaffirms that silence or evasive explanations from an accused in possession of exclusive facts can lead to adverse inference under Section 106.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
1️⃣ Shambhu Nath Mehra v. State of Ajmer (1956)
 Held: Section 106 applies only to facts within the special knowledge of the accused; it does not relieve the prosecution of its primary burden.
 Significance: Foundation for correct use of Section 106, reaffirmed in Anees.
2️⃣ Trimukh Maroti Kirkan v. State of Maharashtra (2006)
 Held: Where the offence occurs in the dwelling shared by the accused and the deceased, and the accused offers no explanation, Section 106 permits inference of guilt.
 Significance: Applied directly to Anees’s situation.
3️⃣ Balvir Singh v. State of Uttarakhand (2022)
 Held: Circumstantial evidence must form a complete and consistent chain to convict; gaps cannot be filled by Section 106 alone.
 Significance: Quoted in Anees for cautionary limits of burden-shifting.


⚖️ CS-24-08 | Anjum Kadari v. Union of India (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 831 | SLP(C) No. 8541/2024
 Judgment Date: 5 November 2024
 Bench: Chief Justice Dr. D.Y. Chandrachud, Justice J.B. Pardiwala and Justice Manoj Misra
 Key Constitutional Articles: 14, 21, 21A, 25–30, 28
 Statutes Involved: U.P. Board of Madarsa Education Act, 2004 and University Grants Commission Act, 1956

🧩 Facts of the Case
The Uttar Pradesh Board of Madarsa Education Act, 2004 (“Madarsa Act”) created a Board to regulate standards of education for roughly 13,000 madarsas educating over 12 lakh students in the State.


The Act oversaw both religious and secular curricula and provided for recognition of qualifications such as Fazil (bachelor’s) and Kamil (post-graduate) degrees.


On 22 March 2024, the Allahabad High Court struck down the entire Act as unconstitutional for allegedly violating Articles 14, 21, 21A, the principle of secularism, and Section 22 of the UGC Act. It also directed the State to shift all madrasa students to schools under the State Education Boards.


Several Special Leave Petitions were filed, leading the Supreme Court to stay the judgment on 5 April 2024 and hear the matter on merits.



⚙️ Issues Before the Court
Whether the Madarsa Act of 2004 is unconstitutional for violating secularism or Articles 14, 21 and 21A of the Constitution.


Whether the State of Uttar Pradesh had legislative competence to enact the Madarsa Act under Entry 25 of List III (Concurrent List).


Whether provisions of the Madarsa Act conflicted with the UGC Act (Entry 66 List I) and were thus beyond State competence.


Whether the High Court was justified in striking down the entire Act rather than applying severability to remove only the invalid parts.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court upheld the constitutional validity of the Madarsa Act except for those provisions relating to the award of higher-education degrees (Fazil and Kamil), which were found to conflict with the UGC Act.


The Court held that the Act is a regulatory statute, enacted under Entry 25 of List III, well within the State’s legislative competence.


The High Court’s wholesale invalidation was set aside; the unconstitutional provisions were severed.


Ratio: A law cannot be struck down for violating abstract constitutional principles such as secularism or democracy; it must contravene a specific constitutional provision or exceed legislative competence. The Madarsa Act validly regulates minority educational institutions so long as it does not encroach upon higher-education standards under the UGC Act.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
1. On Secularism and Constitutional Validity
The Court ruled that no statute can be invalidated merely for violating a “basic-structure” concept like secularism.


Striking down requires violation of a specific constitutional provision or absence of legislative competence.


Secularism, democracy, and federalism are guiding principles, not independent grounds of unconstitutionality.


2. Religious Instruction vs Religious Education
The Court distinguished religious instruction (teaching specific religious practices) from religious education (teaching philosophy of religion).


Article 28 prohibits only religious instruction in State-funded institutions, not religious education or recognition of private institutions offering both religious and secular content.


Therefore, recognising and regulating madarsas does not violate Article 28.


3. Madarsa Act as a Regulatory Statute
The Act aims to raise educational standards, not to promote religion.


Regulation of minority institutions is consistent with Articles 30 and 21A so long as the goal is quality education.


The Right to Education Act (2009) does not apply to minority institutions; hence, Article 21A is not infringed.


4. Legislative Competence
The State has authority under Entry 25 List III (Education) to legislate, even if the institutions offer some religious content.


Excluding education with a religious element from State competence would contradict Article 30, which expressly allows minorities to establish and administer educational institutions.


5. Conflict with UGC Act and Severability
The UGC Act occupies the field of higher-education standards (Entry 66 List I).


Provisions of the Madarsa Act conferring authority to grant Fazil and Kamil degrees were ultra vires, as they intruded upon Parliament’s domain.


These provisions were severable, allowing the remainder of the Act to remain valid.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The Supreme Court set aside the Allahabad High Court’s judgment.


The Madarsa Act was declared constitutionally valid except for its higher-education provisions (Fazil and Kamil degrees).


The State of Uttar Pradesh retains full power to regulate madarsa education up to the secondary level.


Directions were issued for the State to coordinate with the UGC to regularise higher-education equivalence.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Reaffirms that laws cannot be invalidated on abstract basic-structure principles; specific constitutional violation is required.


Clarifies that religious education is not barred under Article 28; regulation of minority institutions is compatible with secularism.


Defines the boundary between State (Entry 25 List III) and Union (Entry 66 List I) competence in education.


Upholds substantive equality by ensuring minority institutions achieve national educational standards.


Demonstrates proper application of doctrine of severability — only unconstitutional provisions struck down, not the entire Act.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
T.M.A. Pai Foundation v. State of Karnataka (2002) – Defined scope of minority educational rights under Article 30.
 Significance: Provided guiding principles for autonomy with regulation.


P.A. Inamdar v. State of Maharashtra (2005) – Clarified permissible regulation of unaided minority institutions.
 Significance: Applied to justify State’s quality-control role.


The Durgah Committee, Ajmer v. Syed Hussain Ali (1961) – Distinguished denominational rights under Article 26 from educational-minority rights under Article 30.
 Significance: Used to demarcate religious administration from educational autonomy.



⚖️ CS-24-09 | Association for Democratic Reforms v. Election Commission of India (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 341 | Writ Petition (Civil) No. 434 of 2023
 Date of Judgment: 26 April 2024
 Bench: Justice Sanjiv Khanna and Justice Dipankar Datta
 Key Statutes / Articles: Articles 14, 19(1)(a), 324 and 326 of the Constitution; Representation of the People Act 1951; Conduct of Elections Rules 1961

🧩 Facts of the Case
The Association for Democratic Reforms (ADR), an NGO, petitioned the Supreme Court questioning the reliability, transparency, and security of Electronic Voting Machines (EVMs) used by the Election Commission of India (ECI).
 They sought either:
a complete return to paper ballots, or


100 percent counting of Voter Verifiable Paper Audit Trail (VVPAT) slips alongside electronic tallies.


Currently, only five randomly selected polling stations per constituency undergo VVPAT verification. The petitioners argued that this limited sample was insufficient to ensure accuracy, and urged that either voters should physically handle their slips or that every vote should be verified through paper.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
Whether the use of EVMs ensures the integrity and security of elections under Articles 324 and 326.


Whether 100 % VVPAT verification is constitutionally or statutorily mandated to guarantee free and fair elections.


Whether returning to paper ballots is feasible, given India’s electoral scale.


What procedural safeguards must be in place to ensure public trust in the EVM-VVPAT system.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court dismissed the petition, upholding the current EVM-VVPAT system. It held that:
The existing mechanism, in which a VVPAT slip is visible to the voter for seven seconds before being sealed, satisfies the constitutional requirement of free and fair elections.
However, the Court issued two new directions to enhance transparency:
Symbol loading units used for configuring VVPATs must be sealed and stored with EVMs for 45 days after elections, with signatures of candidates or representatives.


Candidates finishing second or third may request technical verification of up to five percent of EVMs in their constituency within seven days of result declaration. If tampering is found, the ECI will refund verification costs.



💡 Reasoning of the Court
1. How an EVM Works and Why Manipulation Is Unlikely
An EVM comprises a ballot unit, control unit, and VVPAT.


Candidate names and symbols are physically affixed; the system stores no political data before symbol-loading.


EVMs are not connected to the internet and have neutral firmware that cannot be altered post-manufacture.


Multiple pre-poll safeguards exist: mock polling, sealing, serial-number verification, and multi-party observation.


After voting, EVMs are sealed, guarded, and observed by party agents; results are retrieved only on counting day.
 → Hence, systemic hacking or tampering is impractical and unproven.


2. Rejection of 100 % VVPAT Counting
The Court held that while voters have a right to ensure their vote is recorded and counted, this does not mean every vote must be manually verified.


Expanding verification to all slips would delay results, double manpower, and heighten human error.


No empirical evidence suggested mismatches in the five-station sampling method.


3. No Return to Paper Ballots
Paper-ballot systems are vulnerable to booth capturing, invalid votes, and administrative manipulation, unmanageable with 97 crore voters.


EVMs enhance efficiency, eliminate invalid ballots, and strengthen auditability.


4. Directions for Greater Transparency
The Court encouraged procedural upgrades rather than regression to older methods.


Justices Khanna and Datta emphasised continuous innovation and data-based audit mechanisms to maintain voter confidence.



✅ Decision / Outcome
Petition dismissed.


Current EVM-VVPAT framework upheld.


Two additional safeguards ordered (symbol-loading storage + optional verification).



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Reinforces the principle that constitutional guarantees of free and fair elections demand reasonable reliability, not perfect infallibility.


Defines judicial limits: courts cannot micromanage election technology absent proven systemic failure.


Recognises the ECI’s technical and administrative autonomy under Article 324.


Introduces procedural innovations—verifiable audit trails and candidate-initiated verification—to build public confidence.


Balances transparency and administrative feasibility in modern electoral governance.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Significance
Subramanian Swamy v. Election Commission of India (2013) – Directed ECI to incorporate VVPATs to strengthen transparency; foundation for present regime.


N. Chandrababu Naidu v. Union of India (2019) – Upheld random sample verification in five EVMs per constituency; adopted as standard procedure.


People’s Union for Civil Liberties v. Union of India (2003) – Recognised voter’s right to know as part of Article 19(1)(a); applied analogously to reinforce transparency as democratic necessity.


Kuldip Nayar v. Union of India (2006) – Reaffirmed judicial deference to ECI in electoral procedures.

⚖️ CS-24-10 | Babu Sahebagouda Rudragoudar & Ors. v. State of Karnataka (2024)
Citation: 2024 LiveLaw (SC) 316
 Date of Judgment: 19 April 2024
 Bench: Justices B.R. Gavai and Sandeep Mehta
 Key Statutory Provisions:
Section 302 r/w Sections 34 and 149, Indian Penal Code (1860)


Section 27, Indian Evidence Act (1872)


Section 378, Criminal Procedure Code (1973)



🧩 Facts of the Case
The complainant’s son (the deceased) had gone to construct a bund in their agricultural field with other villagers. On their return to the village, the accused persons appeared and threatened to take revenge for the earlier murder of one Sangound, in which members of the complainant’s family were accused. The accused then attacked and killed the complainant’s son.
 A First Information Report was lodged, and a case was registered against six accused for offences under Sections 143, 147, 148, 302 read with 149 IPC.
The Trial Court found that the prosecution had failed to establish guilt beyond reasonable doubt and acquitted all six accused. The State of Karnataka appealed. The High Court reversed the acquittal for three accused (A-1 to A-3) and convicted them under Section 302 r/w 34 IPC, sentencing them to life imprisonment.
 Aggrieved, the accused approached the Supreme Court challenging the High Court’s reversal of their acquittal.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
Whether the High Court was justified in reversing the acquittal recorded by the Trial Court.


What are the principles governing interference with acquittals by appellate courts under Section 378 CrPC.


Whether the High Court correctly appreciated the evidence and the admissibility of disclosure statements under Section 27 of the Evidence Act.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court set aside the conviction and restored the Trial Court’s acquittal.
Ratio: An appellate court can reverse an acquittal only if the judgment is patently perverse, based on misreading or omission of material evidence, or if no two reasonable views are possible and only the view of guilt can be drawn from the record.
The Court held that the High Court’s interference was unwarranted because the Trial Court’s view was reasonable and based on a correct appreciation of evidence.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
1. Appellate Restraint in Acquittal Appeals
The Supreme Court reiterated that in State appeals, interference with an acquittal is permissible only where the lower court’s finding is manifestly unreasonable or suffers from perversity.


The accused enjoys a double presumption of innocence—first as an accused and again after acquittal.


The High Court erred by re-evaluating the entire evidence and substituting its own conclusions for those of the Trial Court without establishing perversity.


2. Evaluation of Evidence and Motive
The Court observed that the alleged motive of “revenge for Sangound’s death” was double-edged: it could equally have motivated the complainant party to falsely implicate the accused.


This cast serious doubt on the prosecution version.


3. Admissibility of Disclosure Statements (Section 27 Evidence Act)
The Court referred to State of U.P. v. Deoman Upadhyaya (1960) and Ramanand @ Nandlal Bharti v. State of U.P. (2022), clarifying that only that portion of an accused’s statement which distinctly leads to discovery is admissible; the rest is inadmissible.


Mere production of the memorandum prepared by the Investigating Officer without the officer narrating the circumstances of its recording is not proof of its contents.


4. Assessment of Witness Credibility
Inconsistencies and contradictions in witness accounts further weakened the prosecution case.


Hence, the Trial Court’s view acquitting the accused was fully sustainable.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The appeal by the accused was allowed.


The High Court’s judgment was set aside, and the Trial Court’s acquittal was restored.


The accused were released; their bail bonds were discharged.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Reaffirms the limited scope of appellate interference with acquittals — interference is justified only when the Trial Court’s view is perverse or wholly unsustainable.


Highlights the double presumption of innocence principle protecting accused persons after acquittal.


Clarifies the proper evidentiary use of Section 27 Evidence Act—mere formal proof is insufficient without contextual testimony.


Demonstrates judicial caution where motive may operate both ways, making the prosecution case doubtful.


Strengthens jurisprudence on maintaining balance between State’s right to appeal and the sanctity of acquittal judgments.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
State of U.P. v. Deoman Upadhyaya (1960) – Only that portion of an accused’s disclosure leading directly to discovery is admissible.


Ramanand @ Nandlal Bharti v. State of U.P. (2022) – Exhibiting a memorandum alone does not prove its content; Investigating Officer must testify to the facts.


Chandrappa v. State of Karnataka (2007) – Established guiding principles for appellate interference in acquittal appeals.

⚖️ CS-24-11 | Bar of Indian Lawyers through its President Jasbir Singh Malik v. D.K. Gandhi (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC ___ | 2024 LiveLaw (SC) ___
 Date of Judgment: 14 May 2024
 Bench: Justice Bela M. Trivedi and Justice Pankaj Mithal
 Key Statutes:
Consumer Protection Act, 1986 / 2019 – Section 2(1)(o): “Service”


Advocates Act, 1961 – Professional conduct and disciplinary control of advocates



🧩 Background
This case is a landmark pronouncement on whether legal services provided by advocates fall within the ambit of the Consumer Protection Act (CPA). It settles a long-standing conflict between the consumer law regime and the professional-regulatory framework under the Advocates Act, 1961.

⚙️ Facts of the Case
The dispute arose when D.K. Gandhi engaged an advocate to file a complaint under Section 138, Negotiable Instruments Act, 1881, concerning a dishonoured cheque of ₹20,000.


The case was later settled, but Gandhi alleged that the advocate failed to deliver the settlement amount and instead filed a separate suit seeking ₹5,000 as his legal fees.


Gandhi filed a consumer complaint before the District Consumer Forum alleging deficiency in service by the advocate.


The District Forum and later the National Commission held that advocates’ services fall within the definition of “service” under Section 2(1)(o) of the CPA.


The Bar of Indian Lawyers, through its President, challenged this before the Supreme Court, arguing that legal services cannot be treated as consumer services.



⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether legal services rendered by advocates fall within the definition of “service” under Section 2(1)(o) of the Consumer Protection Act.


Whether advocates can be held liable for deficiency in service before consumer fora.


Whether applying consumer law to advocates conflicts with the regulatory scheme of the Advocates Act, 1961.



💼 Arguments
Petitioner (Bar of Indian Lawyers):
The Advocates Act, 1961 provides a comprehensive framework for regulating professional conduct and disciplining advocates; hence, advocates cannot simultaneously be regulated under consumer law.


The relationship between advocate and client is a contract of personal service, not a contract for service — and the latter alone falls within the CPA.


The legal profession is sui generis and cannot be equated with commercial services; outcomes in litigation depend on external judicial and factual contingencies.


Subjecting advocates to CPA jurisdiction would impair professional independence and open floodgates of frivolous complaints from dissatisfied clients.


Respondent (D.K. Gandhi):
Advocates provide paid services, establishing a service provider–consumer relationship; hence, clients must have access to consumer-law remedies.


Excluding advocates would deny clients effective redressal for negligence or misconduct.


Accountability through consumer fora would enhance professional standards, similar to doctors held liable under Indian Medical Association v. V.P. Shantha (1995).


Applying CPA to advocates would not conflict with the Advocates Act but rather complement it by increasing transparency.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court allowed the appeal and set aside the decision of the National Consumer Disputes Redressal Commission (NCDRC).
Held:
 Services rendered by advocates do not fall within the definition of “service” under Section 2(1)(o) of the Consumer Protection Act.
Ratio:
The relationship between an advocate and client is one of trust, confidence, and personal obligation, not a commercial or business arrangement.


Such services constitute a “contract of personal service”, which is expressly excluded from the CPA.


The Advocates Act, 1961 already provides adequate mechanisms to deal with misconduct and negligence through the Bar Council’s disciplinary jurisdiction.


Legal practice is not a trade, business, or profession for commercial gain, but a noble profession governed by ethics and duty to the court and client.



💡 Reasoning of the Court
The Court observed that legal representation often involves factors beyond the advocate’s control — the judge’s discretion, quality of evidence, and procedural complexities.


Hence, equating legal services with market-based services (like banking or insurance) is legally and conceptually flawed.


It reaffirmed that the Consumer Protection Act excludes contracts of personal service, which involve fiduciary relationships rather than purely commercial transactions.


The Court emphasized that the legal profession is sui generis — unique and rooted in public duty — and cannot be treated as an economic service under consumer law.



✅ Decision / Outcome
Advocates’ services are excluded from the Consumer Protection Act.


Consumer complaints alleging deficiency in legal services are not maintainable.


The proper remedy for clients alleging professional misconduct or negligence lies under Sections 35–44 of the Advocates Act, 1961, before the Bar Council.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Establishes a clear demarcation between professional regulation and consumer-law liability.


Upholds the independence and integrity of the legal profession, insulating it from consumer-forum jurisdiction.


Clarifies that legal services are governed by the fiduciary and ethical framework of the Advocates Act, not the commercial framework of the CPA.


Aligns Indian law with the global principle that lawyers owe duties to both clients and courts, not merely contractual obligations.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
Indian Medical Association v. V.P. Shantha (1995) – Distinguished; doctors provide “service” under CPA, but advocates do not, due to the nature of their fiduciary duties.


D.K. Gandhi v. M. Mathias (2007) – Earlier NCDRC precedent including advocates under CPA; overruled.


Vishaka v. State of Rajasthan (1997) – Reiterated the importance of professional ethics and regulatory oversight in professions.

⚖️ CS-24-12 | Bilkis Yakub Rasool v. Union of India (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 24
 Date of Judgment: 8 January 2024
 Bench: Justice B.V. Nagarathna and Justice Ujjal Bhuyan
 Relevant Statutes / Provisions:
Article 32, Constitution of India — Enforcement of Fundamental Rights


Article 14, Constitution of India — Right to Equality


Article 21, Constitution of India — Right to Life and Personal Liberty


Sections 432, 433, 433A, and 432(7), Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 — Remission and commutation of sentences



🧩 Factual Background
The petitioner, Bilkis Yakub Rasool, a survivor of gang rape and communal violence during the 2002 Gujarat riots, challenged the remission orders passed by the State of Gujarat that prematurely released eleven convicts who had been sentenced to life imprisonment for her rape and the murder of her family members.
The case had originally been investigated by the CBI and tried in Mumbai, where the trial court in 2008 convicted the accused and sentenced them to life imprisonment. The Bombay High Court and later the Supreme Court upheld the convictions.
After serving about fourteen years in prison, the convicts applied to the Gujarat Government for remission under its 1992 policy. Relying on an earlier order of the Supreme Court in Radheshyam Bhagwandas Shah v. State of Gujarat (2022), Gujarat granted remission on 10 August 2022. These orders were challenged before the Supreme Court by the petitioner and by public-spirited individuals.

⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether a writ petition by the victim challenging remission was maintainable under Article 32.


Whether public interest litigations (PILs) challenging remission were maintainable.


Whether the State of Gujarat was competent to pass remission orders.


Whether the remission orders were legal and valid under the CrPC.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court allowed the petitions and quashed the remission orders as illegal and void.
Held:
 (1) The writ petition filed by the victim was maintainable under Article 32, as it sought enforcement of fundamental rights under Articles 14 and 21.
 (2) The State of Gujarat lacked jurisdiction under Section 432(7) CrPC because the convicts had been tried and sentenced in Maharashtra; thus, the State of Maharashtra alone was the appropriate government.
 (3) The remission orders of 10 August 2022 were unlawful, having been obtained by fraud upon the Court in the Radheshyam Shah case.
 (4) The convicts were directed to surrender within two weeks to serve the remainder of their life sentences.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
1️⃣ Maintainability of the Writ Petition (Article 32):
The Court rejected the argument that the petitioner should have approached the Gujarat High Court.


Since she sought enforcement of fundamental rights (Articles 14 and 21), she could directly invoke Article 32 before the Supreme Court.


The High Court could not overrule or vary the earlier Supreme Court order in Radheshyam Shah; hence, direct recourse was justified.


2️⃣ Jurisdiction – “Appropriate Government” (Section 432(7) CrPC):
The appropriate government for remission is the one under whose jurisdiction the sentencing court functions, not where the offence was committed or the prisoner is lodged.


Because the convicts were sentenced in Mumbai, the Government of Maharashtra alone had jurisdiction to consider remission.


The Gujarat Government usurped powers not vested in it; hence, its orders were ultra vires the CrPC.


3️⃣ Fraud on the Court – Radheshyam Shah Order:
The convict who obtained the Radheshyam Shah order had suppressed material facts, including that:


His remission plea was already under consideration in Maharashtra, and


The Gujarat 1992 policy had been withdrawn.


The Court held that the Radheshyam Shah direction was procured by fraud and therefore non-est in law.


4️⃣ Rule of Law and Victim’s Rights:
The Court observed that the remission of convicts in heinous crimes eroded public confidence in the justice system.


Liberty cannot be claimed in violation of the rule of law; only lawful liberty is constitutionally protected.


5️⃣ Guiding Principles for Remission:
The Court enumerated non-exhaustive conditions under the CrPC:
Application must be filed before the State of conviction, not of offence.


Compliance with Section 433A CrPC—a life convict must serve at least 14 years before remission.


Opinion of the trial judge is mandatory under Section 432(2).


The policy applicable should be that of the competent State, generally the one in force at the time of conviction.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The remission orders dated 10 August 2022 passed by the Gujarat Government were quashed.


The convicts were ordered to surrender within two weeks.


The Court declared that remission obtained through fraud and want of jurisdiction is null and void ab initio.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Clarifies jurisdiction: The “appropriate government” under Section 432(7) CrPC is the State where the sentence is imposed, not where the crime occurred.


Affirms victim’s standing: Victims can approach the Supreme Court under Article 32 to challenge executive actions infringing their fundamental rights.


Reinforces rule of law: Fraudulent or ultra vires executive acts cannot confer valid liberty.


Sets procedural safeguards: Reinforces that remission is a discretionary privilege, not a legal entitlement.


Promotes accountability: Prevents misuse of remission power in politically or socially sensitive cases.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
Radheshyam Bhagwandas Shah v. State of Gujarat (2022): Directed Gujarat to consider remission — later declared invalid as obtained by fraud.


State of Haryana v. Jagdish (2010): Clarified application of remission policies under Sections 432 and 433A CrPC.


Maru Ram v. Union of India (1981): Laid foundational principles governing remission and commutation under the CrPC.



⚖️ CS-24-13 | Central Organisation for Railway Electrification v. M/S ECI-SPIC-SMO-MCML (JV) & JSW Steel Ltd. v. South Western Railway (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 857 (8 November 2024)
 Bench: Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud, Justices Hrishikesh Roy, P.S. Narasimha, J.B. Pardiwala, and Manoj Misra
 Type: Constitution Bench (Five Judges)
 Relevant Statutes / Provisions:
Section 12(5), Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996: Disqualifies arbitrators who have specified relationships with the parties.


Seventh Schedule, Arbitration Act: Lists categories of relationships leading to ineligibility (e.g., current employment, financial interest, advisory roles).


Section 18, Arbitration Act: Mandates equal treatment of parties in arbitration proceedings.


Article 14, Constitution of India: Equality before law and fairness in State action.


GCC Clauses 64(3)(a) & 64(3)(b): Railway contract clauses allowing appointment of arbitrators — either serving or retired officers, depending on waiver of Section 12(5).



🧩 Background / Facts of the Case
The Central Organisation for Railway Electrification (CORE) entered into contracts with a joint venture (M/S ECI-SPIC-SMO-MCML) for railway electrification. The contract contained a standard General Conditions of Contract (GCC) clause for arbitration, giving CORE authority to nominate arbitrators from its curated panel of serving or retired railway officers.
When disputes arose and CORE terminated the contract, the JV objected to this procedure, asserting that the panel system was unilateral and biased, violating Section 12(5) of the Arbitration Act. The JV instead sought appointment of a neutral sole arbitrator through the Allahabad High Court.
The High Court appointed a retired judge as sole arbitrator. CORE appealed, arguing that the GCC arbitration clause was contractually binding.
The matter was referred to a five-judge Constitution Bench to resolve the conflict among earlier precedents — TRF Ltd. (2017), Perkins Eastman (2019), CORE (2019), and Tantia Constructions (2021) — on whether an ineligible or interested party can nominate arbitrators from its own panel.

⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether a person disqualified under Section 12(5) read with the Seventh Schedule can authorize or mandate appointment of arbitrators from a panel curated by them.


Whether requiring a private party to choose from a State-curated panel of arbitrators violates Section 18 (equality of parties).


Whether unilateral appointment of arbitrators by a government entity violates Article 14 of the Constitution.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
By a 3:2 majority, the Supreme Court held that unilateral appointment of arbitrators by one party, especially a State entity, is impermissible as it violates the principles of equality, impartiality, and independence central to arbitration.
Held:
Clauses allowing one party to appoint or control appointment of arbitrators violate Section 12(5) read with the Seventh Schedule.


PSU or government entities may maintain panels, but requiring the counterparty to choose only from that panel violates Section 18 (equal treatment of parties).


The principle of party autonomy is subject to mandatory statutory safeguards ensuring neutrality and fairness.



💡 Reasoning of the Court
1️⃣ Independence and Impartiality Are Mandatory
The majority (CJI Chandrachud, Pardiwala & Misra JJ.) held that the Arbitration Act’s structure prioritizes neutrality over party autonomy.


Sections 12 and 18 read with Article 14 impose a duty of equal treatment at all stages — including appointment.


Requiring a private party to select from a PSU’s own panel creates an “inequality of arms”, undermining the fairness of the process.


2️⃣ Limitation on Party Autonomy
While party autonomy is foundational, it operates within the limits of statutory fairness.


Any arbitration agreement that undermines impartiality is contrary to the public policy of India and void under Section 34(2)(b)(ii).


3️⃣ Public Contracts and Article 14
In contracts involving State entities, constitutional obligations of fairness and non-arbitrariness apply.


The unilateral appointment of a sole arbitrator by a State party is contrary to Article 14 and public policy.


4️⃣ Minority Opinions (Roy & Narasimha JJ.)
Justice Hrishikesh Roy: Unilateral appointments should not be blanketly prohibited; courts should assess bias under the challenge mechanism (Sections 12–15).


Justice Narasimha: Section 18 (equality of parties) applies after the tribunal is constituted; impartiality can be ensured through existing statutory safeguards.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The High Court’s appointment of a sole arbitrator was set aside.


The Court directed that arbitrators be appointed as per GCC procedure, but excluding serving officers or any person falling under the Seventh Schedule disqualifications.


The 2019 CORE precedent allowing PSU-controlled panel arbitration was overruled.


The majority clarified that public-sector arbitral panels are permissible only if both parties participate equally in the selection process.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Unilateral appointment = impermissible: Reinforces that even contractual consent cannot override statutory impartiality safeguards.


Equal treatment doctrine expanded: Section 18 applies to every stage of arbitration — from appointment to award.


Public policy & Article 14: State entities must ensure fairness in contractual arbitration clauses.


Overrules conflicting precedents: TRF Ltd., Perkins Eastman, and Tantia Constructions now harmonized under this Constitution Bench ruling.


Arbitration reform milestone: Ensures India’s arbitration law aligns with global standards of independence and equality.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
TRF Ltd. v. Energo Engineering Projects Ltd. (2017): Held that an ineligible person cannot nominate another arbitrator.


Perkins Eastman Architects DPC v. HSCC (India) Ltd. (2019): Extended TRF — a party interested in the dispute cannot appoint an arbitrator.


Union of India v. Tantia Constructions (2021): Criticized unilateral PSU appointments; led to the Constitution Bench reference.


JSW Steel Ltd. v. South Western Railway (2024): Heard with the present case; affirmed equality and impartiality principles in PSU arbitrations.


Article 14 Jurisprudence: ONGC v. Afcons Gunanusa JV (2022) reaffirmed the requirement of procedural fairness in State contracts.

⚖️ CS-24-14 | Child in Conflict with Law v. The State of Karnataka (2024)
Citation: 2024 SCC OnLine SC 798
 Date of Judgment: 22 April 2024
 Bench: Justices Rajesh Bindal and C.T. Ravikumar
 Relevant Statutes / Provisions:
Section 14(3), JJ Act 2015 – Time limit for completing preliminary assessment in heinous offences.


Section 15(1), JJ Act 2015 – Assessment of mental and physical capacity of the child and ability to understand consequences.


Section 19, JJ Act 2015 – Transfer of cases by the Juvenile Justice Board to the Children’s Court.


Sections 376(i), 342 IPC and Sections 4–8, POCSO Act 2012 – Alleged offences against the child.



🧩 Factual Background
A Child in Conflict with Law (“CCL”) was accused of rape and related offences under the IPC and the POCSO Act.
 After the child was granted bail, the Juvenile Justice Board (JJB) undertook a preliminary assessment under Section 15 to determine whether he should be tried as a juvenile or transferred for trial as an adult before a Children’s Court.
Initially, the Principal Magistrate recommended adult trial; however, a subsequent full-Board order found that the CCL should be treated as a juvenile.
 The victim’s mother challenged that decision before the High Court under Section 19, arguing that the Board had exceeded the three-month time limit prescribed in Section 14(3).
The Karnataka High Court agreed, directing that the child be tried as an adult.
 The CCL, through his mother, appealed to the Supreme Court, questioning the rigidity of the time-limit and the correctness of the High Court’s direction.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
Whether the three-month period in Section 14(3) of the JJ Act for completing preliminary assessment is mandatory or directory.


Whether failure to complete the assessment within that period vitiates the proceedings against a child accused of heinous offences.


What is the proper balance between procedural timelines and the rehabilitative object of the JJ Act.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court held that the three-month period under Section 14(3) is directory, not mandatory.
 Non-completion of the assessment within that period does not invalidate proceedings or render the Board’s decision void.
Ratio: The purpose of Section 14(3) is to ensure expedition, not to impose an absolute bar. The statute provides no express consequence for non-compliance, unlike other provisions (e.g., Section 14(4) for petty offences). Therefore, timelines must be applied flexibly to uphold substantive justice.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
Legislative Intent and Context:


The JJ Act is a beneficial, child-centric legislation. Its focus is rehabilitation, not punishment.


Rigid procedural interpretation would defeat the Act’s reformative intent.


Nature of Section 14(3):


The provision sets a procedural direction, not a jurisdictional bar.


Absence of penal consequence indicates legislative intent to treat it as directory.


Systemic Practicality:


The preliminary assessment involves coordination between the JJB, investigating officers, and psychological experts.


Delays often occur due to factors beyond the control of the Board or the child.


Balancing Speed and Fairness:


The Court emphasised procedural efficiency with fairness.


Substantive assessment of the child’s maturity, capacity, and understanding must prevail over mechanical adherence to timelines.


Reaffirmation of the Board’s Authority:


The Board retains full jurisdiction to assess the case even after the lapse of three months, provided the inquiry is fair, reasoned, and based on expert inputs.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The Supreme Court set aside the High Court’s order, restoring the JJB’s decision to treat the CCL as a juvenile.


It held that delay beyond three months does not nullify proceedings.


The Board was directed to continue the inquiry in accordance with Sections 14–19 of the JJ Act.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Procedural timelines in the JJ Act are directory, promoting substantive justice over technicality.


Reinforces the rehabilitative philosophy of juvenile justice — prioritising assessment of culpability and maturity.


Clarifies that failure to meet procedural deadlines does not erase jurisdiction of the Board.


Ensures victims’ and children’s rights are balanced within a fair and non-punitive process.


Strengthens child-friendly justice, consistent with India’s obligations under the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
Pratap Singh v. State of Jharkhand (2005) – Clarified the concept of “juvenile” and application of beneficial interpretation.


Barun Chandra Thakur v. Master Bholu (2022) – Discussed standards for preliminary assessment under Section 15 JJ Act.


Shilpa Mittal v. State of NCT Delhi (2020) – Differentiated “heinous” and “serious” offences for children’s trials.


Ravi v. State of Maharashtra (2019) – Stressed procedural fairness in juvenile proceedings.


State of Punjab v. Gurmit Singh (1996) – Reiterated the need for sensitivity in trials involving sexual offences.



⚖️ CS-24-15 | Cox and Kings Ltd. v. SAP India Pvt. Ltd. (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 708 (also reported as 2023 INSC 1051, Constitution Bench)
 Bench: Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud, Justices Hrishikesh Roy, P.S. Narasimha, J.B. Pardiwala and Manoj Misra
 Date of Judgment: 26 March 2024
 Type: Constitution Bench (Five Judges)
Relevant Provisions:
Section 7, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996 — Definition of arbitration agreement.


Section 11, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996 — Appointment of arbitrators.


Group of Companies Doctrine (GoCD) — Principle allowing non-signatories within a corporate group to be included in arbitration proceedings under specific conditions.



🧩 Background and Facts
In 2010, Cox & Kings Ltd. (C&K) entered into a software licensing agreement with SAP India Pvt. Ltd. for installation of SAP’s “Hybris Solution” software.


In 2015, further project-implementation and support agreements were signed — one of which contained an arbitration clause.


The project failed due to repeated delays, prompting C&K to terminate the contract and seek a refund of ₹ 45 crore.


SAP India countered that termination was wrongful and sought ₹ 17 crore in damages.


Later, C&K initiated a fresh arbitration under Section 11 of the Arbitration Act, naming not only SAP India but also its German parent company, SAP SE, as a party — although SAP SE was not a signatory to the arbitration agreement.


C&K argued that SAP SE had actively supervised the project and thus impliedly consented to be bound by the arbitration clause.


SAP SE denied this, stating it was only a technical advisor and never a contracting party.



⚙️ Issues Before the Court
Whether non-signatories may be bound by an arbitration agreement under Indian law.


Whether the Group of Companies Doctrine forms part of Indian arbitration jurisprudence.


What degree of participation or intention must be shown to infer consent by a non-signatory.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Constitution Bench affirmed that the Group of Companies Doctrine (GoCD) forms part of Indian arbitration law and clarified its limits.
Ratio: A non-signatory may be bound by an arbitration agreement when objective evidence shows it intended to be bound, either through conduct, participation in contract performance, or involvement in negotiation and execution that demonstrates a common intention within the corporate group.
The Court held that mere corporate affiliation or assistance is not sufficient.


The inquiry must determine whether the non-signatory was directly and substantially involved in the contractual relationship giving rise to the dispute.


The Court allowed inclusion of SAP SE in the arbitration, finding that its substantive control and direct involvement implied consent to the arbitration agreement.


Accordingly, an arbitrator was appointed under Section 11 to include SAP SE as a party to the proceedings.



💡 Reasoning of the Court
Consent and Conduct — While written consent remains central under Section 7, the Court observed that in modern commercial arrangements, consent can also be inferred from objective conduct indicating participation and control over the contract.


Group as Single Economic Entity — When members of a corporate group function as a single economic unit, with common management and shared commercial objectives, the law may recognize them as a “single economic reality” for arbitral purposes.


Limitations and Safeguards — The doctrine must be applied narrowly to prevent arbitrary inclusion of non-signatories. Courts must find clear intention and direct involvement before binding them to arbitration.


Doctrine in Comparative Law — Indian law is now aligned with international practice (e.g., Dow Chemical v. Isover Saint-Gobain [ICC Case 4131/1982]) and Singapore jurisprudence recognizing GoCD under specific circumstances.


Dissent (Narasimha J.) — Cautioned that extending arbitration to non-signatories may erode party autonomy and Section 7’s requirement of “agreement in writing.” He advocated strict consent in writing to preserve contractual certainty.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The Supreme Court held that SAP SE’s significant role in contract management and direct participation in performance amounted to implied consent.


SAP SE was accordingly joined as a party to the arbitration.


The Court directed appointment of an arbitrator under Section 11, holding that Indian arbitration law now expressly recognizes GoCD.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
GoCD is part of Indian law: Non-signatories can be bound if their conduct shows a clear intention to be party to the arbitration agreement.


Consent remains foundational: Implied consent must be proved through active involvement or direct benefit from the contract.


Promotes commercial realism: Recognizes modern corporate groups functioning as integrated units.


Restrains over-extension: Mere ownership or association does not create arbitral liability.


Aligns Indian law with international arbitral standards and UNCITRAL principles on consent and intention.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
Chloro Controls India (P) Ltd. v. Severn Trent Water Purification Inc. (2013) – Introduced GoCD to Indian law for composite transactions.


Ameet Lalchand Shah v. Rishabh Enterprises (2018) – Expanded the scope of arbitration to inter-linked commercial agreements.


MTNL v. Canara Bank (2020) – Recognized binding effect on non-signatories based on mutual intention and common transaction.


Dow Chemical v. Isover Saint-Gobain (1982, ICC) – Seminal foreign precedent acknowledging GoCD.


Cheran Properties v. Kasturi & Sons (2018) – Held that arbitral awards can bind non-signatories if they were direct participants.



⚖️ CS-24-16 | Dablu Kujur v. State of Jharkhand (2024)
Citation: 2024 LiveLaw (SC) 227
 Date of Judgment: 12 March 2024
 Bench: Justices Bela M. Trivedi and Pankaj Mithal
 Relevant Statute:
Section 173(2), Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (CrPC) – Contents and requirements of the final police report (chargesheet).



🧩 Factual Background
The appellant, Dablu Kujur, had sought bail after the Jharkhand High Court rejected his application in connection with a murder case.
 When the matter reached the Supreme Court, the Court not only examined the merits of bail but also addressed the procedural compliance of the chargesheet filed by the investigating agency under Section 173(2) CrPC.
The Court used this opportunity to reiterate the mandatory components that a final police report (chargesheet) must contain when forwarded to the Magistrate after investigation.

⚙️ Issues Before the Court
What constitutes a valid “final report” under Section 173(2) of the CrPC?


Whether failure to comply with Section 173(2) requirements affects the court’s power to take cognizance or impacts the fairness of investigation?


Whether the accused (appellant) was entitled to bail based on alleged procedural deficiencies in the investigation report?



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court dismissed the bail appeal and held that a chargesheet is effectively the final report of the police under Section 173(2) CrPC, and must strictly adhere to the statutory requirements.
Ratio: Only a report submitted in conformity with Section 173(2) CrPC can form the lawful basis for a Magistrate to take cognizance. The report must include all the particulars prescribed under the provision and the form specified by the State Government.

💡 Key Findings / Reasoning
The Court emphasized that every police report must contain the following details under Section 173(2):
a. Names of the parties;
 b. Nature of the information;
 c. Names of persons acquainted with the case circumstances;
 d. Whether any offence appears to have been committed, and by whom;
 e. Whether the accused has been arrested;
 f. Whether the accused has been released on bond, with or without surety;
 g. Whether the accused has been forwarded in custody under Section 170 CrPC; and
 h. In cases of sexual offences, whether the medical examination report of the victim has been attached (for offences under Sections 376, 376A–E IPC).
Additionally, the Court highlighted that:
Section 172 CrPC requires that every investigating officer must maintain a case diary, recording day-to-day progress.


Sub-section (1A) mandates that statements under Section 161 CrPC be inserted in the diary.


Sub-section (1B) requires that diaries be paginated and properly maintained as a bound volume.


These procedural steps ensure transparency, accountability, and judicial scrutiny of investigations.

✅ Decision / Outcome
The bail application was denied, given the gravity of the offence and the advanced stage of trial.


The Court issued a direction to all investigating officers to ensure strict compliance with Section 173(2) when forwarding police reports to Magistrates.


It clarified that only a procedurally complete report can be treated as the basis for cognizance, and incomplete reports can compromise the fairness of criminal proceedings.



🌟 Significance / Key Takeaways
Chargesheet = Final Report: Reinforces that the “chargesheet” under common parlance is the final police report under Section 173(2) CrPC.


Mandatory particulars: Enumerates what every police report must contain before submission.


Compliance with Section 172: Reaffirms that daily case diaries and witness statements form the backbone of proper investigation records.


Fair investigation principle: Strengthens procedural integrity by ensuring courts receive complete, verified investigation reports before taking cognizance.


Administrative guidance: Serves as a reminder for investigative agencies to follow procedural law meticulously to uphold due process.



🔗 Referred / Related Provisions and Precedents
Section 173(2), CrPC – Governs police reports post-investigation; foundational for cognizance.


Section 172, CrPC – Mandates maintenance of a case diary.


Bhagwant Singh v. Commissioner of Police (1985) – Recognized the right of the informant to notice when the report recommends closure.


Union of India v. Prafulla Kumar Samal (1979) – Clarified the role of the Magistrate in assessing a police report.


State of Bihar v. Ramesh Singh (1977) – Established that chargesheets must contain sufficient material to justify cognizance.

⚖️ CS-24-17 | Devu G. Nair v. The State of Kerala (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 228
Date of Judgment: 11 March 2024
Bench: Chief Justice Dr. D.Y. Chandrachud, Justice J.B. Pardiwala, and Justice Manoj Misra

📘 Legal Context
The case concerns the scope of habeas corpus petitions under Article 226 when used to secure the liberty of adults in same-sex relationships, and the constitutional protection of autonomy, dignity, and identity under Articles 14, 15, and 21. It also addresses judicial sensitivity in matters involving the LGBTQ+ community and the impermissibility of counselling that seeks to alter a person’s sexual orientation.

🧩 Factual Background
The appellant, Devu G. Nair, was in a consensual same-sex relationship with another woman, referred to as “X.” Nair alleged that “X” was being unlawfully confined by her parents, who opposed their relationship, and filed a writ of habeas corpus before the Kerala High Court seeking her release.
The High Court directed the Secretary of the District Legal Services Authority (DLSA) to record “X’s” statement at her parents’ house and also ordered that “X” undergo counselling at an authorised centre.
Nair approached the Supreme Court, contending that such counselling violated “X’s” autonomy and that taking her statement in parental custody was coercive. She argued that the High Court’s directions undermined the principle of personal liberty and sexual identity, guaranteed under the Constitution.
The Supreme Court directed “X’s” parents to produce her before the Family Court, Kollam, and appointed Ms. Saleena V.G. Nair, a member of the Supreme Court e-Committee, to independently interact with “X.” The report submitted by the Family Court and Ms. Nair indicated that “X” voluntarily chose to reside with her parents, wished to focus on her career, and described the appellant as an intimate friend, not a partner she wished to live with at that time.

⚖️ Issues
Whether the habeas corpus petition filed by Devu G. Nair was maintainable to secure the liberty of her same-sex partner.


Whether the High Court erred in directing counselling for “X,” thereby interfering with her personal autonomy.


What safeguards courts must follow when handling habeas corpus petitions involving LGBTQ+ individuals.



🏛 Judgment and Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court upheld the finding that “X” was not in illegal detention and that she voluntarily chose to stay with her parents. However, it criticised the High Court’s counselling order as potentially coercive and issued broad constitutional guidelines to ensure that habeas corpus proceedings are conducted with sensitivity and respect for the autonomy and dignity of LGBTQ+ individuals.
Ratio:
Courts must respect the personal liberty, autonomy, and sexual identity of adults in consensual same-sex relationships. Counselling or judicial intervention cannot be used to modify, suppress, or question one’s sexual orientation or relationship choices.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
The Court observed that ordering counselling or supervision over the choices of consenting adults amounts to judicial paternalism and infringes upon Article 21 rights. It clarified that constitutional morality, not social morality, must guide judicial behavior.
The Court stressed that in habeas corpus cases involving intimate relationships, the judicial inquiry must end once free will is established. Judges cannot attempt to “reform,” “correct,” or “redirect” individuals based on their orientation or relationship.
The Court also recognised that the concept of family is not limited to the natal or biological family. For LGBTQ+ persons, “family” includes chosen partners and support networks. Judicial institutions must understand and respect these chosen families when dealing with liberty and protection petitions.

📜 Guidelines Issued by the Supreme Court
The Supreme Court, while disposing of the appeal, laid down comprehensive guidelines for courts and authorities to follow in similar cases:
Priority and Speed: Habeas corpus and protection petitions involving consenting adults must be given top priority to avoid delay and further unlawful confinement.


Free and Voluntary Interaction: Judges must ensure that they speak to the detainee in-camera in an atmosphere free from coercion, family pressure, or social influence.


Privacy and Safety: Proceedings must ensure confidentiality and dignity of the individuals concerned.


No Coercive Counselling: Counselling cannot aim to change the detainee’s sexual orientation or identity.


Empathy and Neutrality: Judges must remain sensitive and neutral, avoiding any homophobic or transphobic bias.


Immediate Relief: If unlawful confinement is established, the person must be released immediately and, if necessary, granted police protection.


Judicial Restraint: Courts must confine their role to determining free will, not moral judgment or “reform.”


Respect for Identity: Judges and lawyers must avoid derogatory references or assumptions about gender identity or sexuality.



✅ Decision
The Supreme Court did not interfere with the High Court’s factual finding that “X” voluntarily chose to stay with her parents. However, it set aside the counselling direction and clarified the constitutional position that courts must never use such measures to influence sexual orientation or personal choices.
The Court reaffirmed that the dignity, identity, and liberty of LGBTQ+ persons are constitutionally protected and that judicial institutions must act as guardians of autonomy, not as moral arbiters.

🌟 Significance and Key Takeaways
This judgment strengthens India’s evolving constitutional jurisprudence on sexual orientation, personal autonomy, and equality. It is one of the first Supreme Court rulings post-Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India (2018) to apply these principles to judicial procedure, not merely criminal law.
The ruling establishes that counselling cannot override consent, and that courts must prioritise individual will over familial or societal expectations. It also broadens the meaning of family to include non-traditional and chosen relationships.

🔗 Related Precedents and Conceptual Connections
The decision builds upon key constitutional precedents:
Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India (2018): Decriminalised same-sex relations and affirmed LGBTQ+ dignity and autonomy.


Shafin Jahan v. Asokan K.M. (2018): Held that adult individuals have an unfettered right to choose their partners.


K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017): Recognised privacy and decisional autonomy as fundamental to Article 21.


Deepika Singh v. Central Administrative Tribunal (2022): Expanded the concept of “family” to include unmarried and non-traditional relationships.


S. Khushboo v. Kanniammal (2010): Affirmed the constitutional protection of personal life choices against moral scrutiny.



⚖️ CS-24-18 | Dolly Rani v. Manish Kumar Chanchal (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 412 | Decided on: 3 May 2024
Bench: Justice B.V. Nagarathna and Justice Augustine George Masih

📘 Legal Context & Relevant Provisions
Section 7, Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 — A Hindu marriage becomes valid only upon solemnisation by customary rites and ceremonies, including saptapadi (seven steps) where applicable.


Section 8, Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 — Permits registration of a marriage, but only after a valid marriage has already been solemnised. Registration is evidentiary, not constitutive.


Article 142, Constitution of India — Empowers the Supreme Court to issue orders or decrees to do complete justice between parties.



🧩 Factual Background
The appellant, Dolly Rani, and the respondent, Manish Kumar Chanchal, claimed to have been married in July 2021 based on a certificate issued by the “Vadik Jankalyan Samiti (Regd.)”.


However, a formal Hindu marriage ceremony, which was planned for 25 October 2022, was never performed due to disputes between the parties.


Despite the absence of a traditional ceremony, both individuals obtained a marriage registration certificate and later initiated multiple proceedings against each other — including criminal cases and petitions under the Hindu Marriage Act.


Subsequently, both parties approached the Supreme Court jointly, seeking:


A declaration that no valid marriage ever existed;


Cancellation of the registration certificates;


Quashing of all pending civil and criminal proceedings based on that marriage.



⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether registration under Section 8 of the Hindu Marriage Act can create a valid marriage in the absence of solemnisation as required under Section 7.


Whether the issuance of a registration certificate confers upon the parties the legal status of husband and wife.


Whether the Supreme Court can invoke Article 142 to declare such a marriage void ab initio and quash all related proceedings.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court held that solemnisation under Section 7 is a mandatory condition for a valid Hindu marriage.
Without performance of customary rites such as saptapadi, no marriage can be said to have taken place in the eyes of law.
Accordingly, registration alone does not create a marital relationship — it merely records an existing valid marriage.
Ratio: Registration under Section 8 cannot validate a marriage that was never solemnised. The ceremony is the foundation; registration is only proof.
The Court declared that the purported marriage between the parties was void ab initio, as it was never solemnised in accordance with Hindu customs.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
Sanctity of Solemnisation (Section 7)


The Court reiterated that Hindu marriage is not merely a contractual arrangement but a sacramental union (samskara).


The expression “solemnised” in Section 7 implies the performance of traditional rituals with the intention of entering into a marital relationship.


The absence of such ceremonies makes the registration a nullity, incapable of conferring legal status.


Registration as Evidentiary, Not Constitutive (Section 8)


Registration serves only to evidence an already solemnised marriage.


The Court observed an increasing misuse of registration mechanisms by individuals registering unperformed marriages for administrative or immigration purposes, warning that this undermines the sanctity of marriage laws.


Exercise of Article 142 Powers


Using its plenary powers under Article 142, the Supreme Court quashed:


The marriage registration certificate,


All pending civil and criminal proceedings, including divorce and maintenance petitions, as no legal marriage ever existed.


The Court stated that invoking Article 142 was necessary to ensure complete justice between the parties and prevent further misuse of judicial process.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The Supreme Court held that no valid marriage ever existed between the parties.


The purported marriage certificate was declared null and void ab initio.


All associated legal proceedings — including divorce petitions, maintenance claims, and criminal complaints — were quashed.


The Court emphasised that registration cannot substitute solemnisation, reaffirming the traditional and statutory requirements of Hindu marriage.



🌟 Significance & Key Takeaways
Reaffirms that a valid Hindu marriage must first be solemnised, not merely registered.


Clarifies that registration is evidentiary — it cannot cure the absence of rituals or ceremonies.


Prevents misuse of the marriage registration process for ulterior purposes such as property, visa, or legal advantage.


Demonstrates the Supreme Court’s use of Article 142 to prevent injustice and clarify matrimonial law.


Strengthens jurisprudence distinguishing between marriage as a social-sacramental institution and registration as a procedural formality.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
Seema v. Ashwani Kumar (2006): Directed states to make marriage registration compulsory for record purposes but did not alter the requirement of solemnisation.


Yamunabai Anantrao Adhav v. Anantrao Shivram Adhav (1988): Held that a void marriage cannot confer marital status or rights under personal law.


Kanwal Ram v. Himachal Pradesh Administration (1966): Clarified that proof of marriage requires evidence of actual solemnisation under Section 7.


Asha Rani v. Rajendra Kumar (2013): Reiterated that registration is merely proof and not validation of a marriage.


Sarla Mudgal v. Union of India (1995): Explained the importance of ceremony and intention in Hindu marriages.

⚖️ CS-24-19 | Dr. Bhim Rao Ambedkar Vichar Manch Bihar v. State of Bihar & Ors. (2024)
Citation: 2024 SCC OnLine SC 523 | Decided on: 17 May 2024
Bench: Justice Vikram Nath and Justice Prashant Kumar Mishra

📘 Legal Context & Relevant Constitutional Provisions
Article 341, Constitution of India: Empowers the President to specify the castes, races, or tribes to be deemed as Scheduled Castes for any State or Union Territory.


Article 341(2): Provides that the list of Scheduled Castes may be modified only by Parliament, through legislation.


Article 366(24): Defines the term Scheduled Castes.


Principle of Constitutional Federalism: Limits the powers of States in modifying centrally notified Scheduled Caste or Scheduled Tribe lists.



🧩 Factual Background
The Government of Bihar, through a Resolution dated 1 July 2015, decided to merge the “Tanti-Tantwa” community, which was originally listed under the Extremely Backward Class (EBC) category, into the list of Scheduled Castes (SC).


The State issued administrative directions allowing “Tanti-Tantwa” members to avail benefits under the SC quota, even though no amendment had been enacted by Parliament to modify the Scheduled Caste list for Bihar.


The petitioner, Dr. Bhim Rao Ambedkar Vichar Manch, a socio-legal organisation, challenged this decision before the Supreme Court, arguing that:


The State had no constitutional authority to alter or expand the SC list;


The move violated Article 341(1) and 341(2); and


The resolution discriminated against genuine Scheduled Castes by illegally redistributing reservation benefits.


The State defended its decision on grounds of social justice and administrative convenience, claiming that the “Tanti-Tantwa” group shared similar socio-economic disadvantages as existing Scheduled Castes.



⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether a State Government has the constitutional competence to include, delete, or merge any community in the Scheduled Caste list notified under Article 341(1).


Whether the Bihar Government’s Resolution dated 01.07.2015 merging the Tanti-Tantwa community into the Scheduled Caste list was constitutionally valid.


What relief, if any, should be granted to persons who had already received benefits under the invalid resolution.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court quashed the Bihar Government’s Resolution of 01.07.2015, holding it unconstitutional and void ab initio.
The Court reaffirmed that the State Government has no power under the Constitution to alter, amend, or merge communities into the Scheduled Caste list.
Ratio: Only Parliament, by law enacted under Article 341(2)**, can modify or expand the list of Scheduled Castes. State Governments possess no executive or legislative competence to alter such lists unilaterally.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
Constitutional Scheme under Article 341:


The power to identify and notify Scheduled Castes lies solely with the President, and any modification requires a Parliamentary enactment.


Once the Presidential Notification is issued, States cannot make additions, deletions, or modifications to the notified list.


Violation of Federal Division of Powers:


The State’s resolution intruded into a Union List subject—matters relating to Scheduled Castes under Article 341 fall within the exclusive domain of Parliament.


Any such unilateral modification by a State would violate the principle of cooperative federalism and constitutional separation of powers.


Doctrine of Constitutional Supremacy:


The Constitution creates an exhaustive procedure for classification of Scheduled Castes.


Allowing States to alter the list would undermine national uniformity and consistency in reservation policies.


Equitable Relief to Affected Individuals:


The Court, acknowledging the equity principle, held that persons who had already benefited under the invalid State Resolution in good faith should not be penalised retroactively.


However, all future benefits under the Scheduled Caste quota must revert to the constitutionally recognised SC categories.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The Bihar Government’s Resolution dated 1 July 2015 was declared unconstitutional and quashed.


The Court directed:


The “Tanti-Tantwa” community to be restored to their original EBC category.


All Scheduled Caste quota posts occupied by “Tanti-Tantwa” members to be returned to genuine SC categories prospectively.


The Court also instructed that no State Government shall issue administrative directions altering the SC/ST lists without a Parliamentary amendment.



🌟 Significance & Key Takeaways
Clarifies Constitutional Competence: The judgment definitively holds that States cannot alter Scheduled Caste or Scheduled Tribe lists.


Reinforces Federal Boundaries: Upholds the exclusive authority of Parliament under Article 341(2).


Protects Integrity of Reservation System: Prevents dilution of Scheduled Caste benefits through arbitrary inclusion of non-SC groups.


Ensures Equitable Transition: Balances constitutional legality with fairness to individuals who had availed benefits in good faith.


Strengthens Rule of Law: Reaffirms that constitutional procedure cannot be replaced by administrative expediency.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
State of Maharashtra v. Keshao Vishwanath Sonone (2021) 13 SCC 336: The Court held that benefits granted under an invalid government order may, on equitable grounds, be protected retrospectively to prevent undue hardship.


E.V. Chinnaiah v. State of Andhra Pradesh (2005) 1 SCC 394: Ruled that States cannot sub-classify or reorganise Scheduled Castes notified under Article 341.


B. Basavalingappa v. D. Munichinnappa (1965) 1 SCR 316: Reiterated that inclusion/exclusion in the SC list lies solely with the President and Parliament.


Indra Sawhney v. Union of India (1992) Supp (3) SCC 217: Distinguished backward class reservations from Scheduled Caste/Tribe lists, emphasising separate constitutional frameworks.


Marri Chandra Shekhar Rao v. Dean, S.G.S. Medical College (1990) 3 SCC 130: Affirmed that Scheduled Caste status is determined by residence and Presidential notification, not by State discretion.

⚖️CS-24-20 | Dr. Brajendra Singh Chauhan & Ors. v. Central Administrative Tribunal & Ors. (2024)
Citation: 2024 SCC OnLine All 954 | Decided on: 4 June 2024
Bench: Justice Vivek Kumar Birla and Justice Donadi Ramesh

📘 Legal Context & Relevant Provisions
Section 17, Administrative Tribunals Act, 1985: Empowers the Central Administrative Tribunal (CAT) to exercise the same jurisdiction and powers as a High Court under the Contempt of Courts Act, 1971 in matters concerning its orders.


Section 19, Contempt of Courts Act, 1971: Provides for an appeal to the Supreme Court from any order or decision of a tribunal exercising contempt jurisdiction.


Articles 226 & 227, Constitution of India: Confer writ and supervisory jurisdiction on High Courts.


Article 323-A, Constitution of India: Establishes administrative tribunals for adjudicating service disputes.



🧩 Factual Background
The petitioners, including Dr. Brajendra Singh Chauhan, were selected for appointment as Assistant Medical Officers pursuant to a favourable order passed by the Central Administrative Tribunal (CAT).


When the administrative authorities allegedly failed to comply fully with the CAT’s directions, the petitioners filed a contempt petition before the CAT under Section 17 of the Administrative Tribunals Act, 1985.


The CAT, after hearing the matter, found that its earlier order had been substantially complied with and dismissed the contempt petition.


Dissatisfied, the petitioners approached the Allahabad High Court under Article 226, challenging the CAT’s dismissal of the contempt application.



⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether a writ petition under Article 226 is maintainable against an order of the CAT passed under contempt jurisdiction.


Whether the only remedy against such contempt orders lies in appeal to the Supreme Court under Section 19 of the Contempt of Courts Act.


Whether the scope of judicial review under Article 226 extends to orders passed by tribunals in the exercise of contempt powers.



🏛  Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Allahabad High Court dismissed the writ petition as not maintainable, holding that:
“An order passed by the Central Administrative Tribunal under its contempt jurisdiction is appealable only to the Supreme Court under Section 19 of the Contempt of Courts Act, 1971, and cannot be challenged before the High Court under Article 226.”

💡 Reasoning of the Court
Exclusive Appellate Remedy under Section 19:


The CAT derives its contempt powers from Section 17 of the Administrative Tribunals Act, which expressly equates the Tribunal’s powers to those of a High Court under the Contempt of Courts Act.


Since Section 19 of the Contempt Act provides a specific appeal mechanism to the Supreme Court, this is the exclusive statutory remedy.


Bar on Invoking Article 226 Jurisdiction:


The High Court relied on T. Sudhakar Prasad v. Government of A.P. (2001) 1 SCC 516, which held that orders passed by tribunals in contempt jurisdiction are not subject to writ interference.


Judicial review under Articles 226 and 227 cannot substitute or bypass a specific statutory appeal provided by Parliament.


L. Chandra Kumar Principle Applied:


While L. Chandra Kumar v. Union of India (1997) preserved the power of judicial review over tribunal decisions, it clarified that such review applies to decisions rendered in original jurisdiction, not contempt orders that are separately governed by statute.


Nature of Contempt Jurisdiction:


Contempt jurisdiction is quasi-criminal, aimed at enforcing the authority of the Tribunal and ensuring compliance with its orders.


Such jurisdiction operates independently from the service matter itself and is not open to collateral challenge via writ petitions.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The writ petition was dismissed as not maintainable.


The Court clarified that:


The exclusive appellate forum against a CAT contempt order lies with the Supreme Court under Section 19 of the Contempt of Courts Act, 1971.


High Courts cannot entertain writ petitions or supervisory proceedings under Articles 226/227 in such matters.


The petitioners were advised to seek remedy directly before the Supreme Court.



🌟 Significance & Key Takeaways
Clarifies appellate hierarchy: Only the Supreme Court has appellate jurisdiction over CAT’s contempt orders.


Limits writ jurisdiction: Reinforces judicial discipline — High Courts cannot re-open CAT contempt findings.


Upholds legislative intent: Parliament’s intent in Section 19 is to ensure a direct route to the Supreme Court for contempt appeals, maintaining procedural uniformity.


Distinguishes between service jurisdiction and contempt jurisdiction: CAT’s service decisions are subject to High Court judicial review, but its contempt decisions are not.


Strengthens administrative justice framework: Ensures finality and efficiency in enforcement of tribunal orders.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
T. Sudhakar Prasad v. Govt. of A.P. (2001) 1 SCC 516: Held that tribunals’ contempt powers are equivalent to those of High Courts, and appeals lie directly to the Supreme Court.


L. Chandra Kumar v. Union of India (1997) 3 SCC 261: Upheld judicial review of tribunal orders but excluded contempt jurisdiction from High Court’s purview.


Union of India v. R. Gandhi (2010) 11 SCC 1: Recognised tribunals as substitutes for High Courts within limited fields but under constitutional supervision.


Jasbir Singh v. State of Punjab (2006) 8 SCC 294: Reiterated that when a statute provides a complete mechanism for appeal, the writ remedy should not be invoked.


Baradakanta Mishra v. Registrar of Orissa High Court (1974) 1 SCC 374: Distinguished contempt jurisdiction as sui generis and autonomous.

⚖️ CS-24-21 | Frank Vitus v. Narcotics Control Bureau (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 412 | Decided on: 22 April 2024
Bench: Justice Abhay S. Oka and Justice Ujjal Bhuyan

📘 Legal Context & Relevant Provisions
Article 21, Constitution of India: Right to life and personal liberty — includes the right to privacy and fair trial.


Section 37 & 52, Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Act, 1985:


Section 37 — limits on granting bail in NDPS cases;


Section 52 — obligations relating to arrest and forwarding of accused.


Section 437(3), Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973: Permits imposition of reasonable bail conditions to ensure attendance and prevent misuse of liberty.



🧩 Factual Background
The appellant, Frank Vitus, a Nigerian national, was arrested and prosecuted under Sections 8, 22, 23, and 29 of the NDPS Act for alleged possession, production, and trafficking of narcotic substances.


The trial court granted bail but imposed two unique conditions:


The appellant must obtain a Certificate of Assurance from the Nigerian High Commission guaranteeing his presence during trial.


He must drop a live location PIN on Google Maps to allow continuous monitoring by the Investigating Officer.


Vitus challenged these bail conditions before the Supreme Court, arguing that they were unreasonable, invasive, and violative of Article 21, as they infringed his right to privacy and imposed disproportionate restrictions.



⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether requiring an accused to share their live location via Google Maps constitutes an unconstitutional invasion of privacy under Article 21.


Whether mandating a foreign national to obtain a certificate of assurance from their embassy as a condition for bail is legally permissible and reasonable.


What are the permissible limits under Section 437(3) CrPC regarding conditions that may accompany a bail order?



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court partly modified the bail conditions, holding that:
The Google Maps tracking condition was unreasonable, ineffective, and violative of privacy rights under Article 21.


The requirement to obtain a certificate from the Nigerian High Commission was disproportionate and impractical for bail compliance.


Courts must ensure bail conditions are rational, proportionate, and non-intrusive, aligned with the objectives of Section 437(3) CrPC.



💡 Reasoning of the Court
On Google Maps Tracking:


The Court held that requiring the accused to drop a live PIN on Google Maps was a technically flawed and legally unsound condition.


Such tracking does not provide real-time updates or serve the purpose of ensuring attendance in trial.


It amounts to constant surveillance, violating the right to privacy as recognized in K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017).


On Embassy Certificate Requirement:


The Court found the demand for a High Commission certificate discriminatory and excessive, particularly against foreign nationals.


While acknowledging the legitimate concern of ensuring presence, it directed less intrusive alternatives — e.g., surrendering passport, regular reporting to police, or furnishing local sureties.


It clarified that such a requirement should be case-specific, not a general rule for all foreign nationals.


On Reasonable Bail Conditions (Section 437(3) CrPC):


Bail conditions must strike a balance between individual liberty and societal interest.


Conditions that are arbitrary, onerous, or technologically unreliable are unconstitutional.


The purpose of conditions is to ensure attendance at trial and prevent obstruction of justice, not to restrict liberty beyond necessity.



✅ Decision / Outcome
The Supreme Court removed both disputed conditions:


The Google Maps PIN condition was struck down as unconstitutional.


The High Commission certificate was declared optional and to be applied only where practical.


The Court substituted these with conventional bail terms:


The appellant must surrender his passport and report weekly to the NCB office.


Any future bail conditions must comply with Section 437(3) CrPC and Article 21 safeguards.



🌟 Significance & Key Takeaways
Affirms Privacy as Core to Liberty: Any surveillance-based bail condition must meet strict tests of necessity and proportionality.


Sets Precedent on Bail Conditions for Foreign Nationals: Courts cannot impose embassy-related conditions as a rule; practicality and fairness must prevail.


Reiterates Judicial Restraint: Bail conditions must be reasonable and non-punitive — courts cannot impose measures resembling custody.


Protects the Dignity of Accused Persons: Upholds that even in NDPS cases, human rights and fair trial standards remain paramount.


Strengthens Article 21 Jurisprudence: Aligns bail jurisprudence with constitutional values of privacy, dignity, and procedural fairness.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
Kunal Kumar Tiwari v. State of Bihar (2018): On imposing conditions for bail of foreign nationals under NDPS; emphasized proportionality.


Munish Bhasin v. State (NCT of Delhi) (2009): Held that bail conditions must not be arbitrary or unnecessarily onerous.


State of A.P. v. Challa Ramakrishna Reddy (2000): Reiterated that Article 21 applies even to prisoners — liberty cannot be curtailed without fair procedure.


Supreme Court Legal Aid Committee v. Union of India (1994): Laid down liberal guidelines for granting bail to undertrial prisoners in NDPS cases.


K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017) 10 SCC 1: Recognized privacy as a fundamental right intrinsic to dignity and liberty.


