⚖️ CS-24-22 | Gaurav Kumar v. Union of India (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 612 | Decided on: 12 June 2024
 Bench: Chief Justice Dr. D.Y. Chandrachud and Justice J.B. Pardiwala

📘 Relevant Provisions
Section 24(1)(f), Advocates Act, 1961 — fixes enrolment fees payable by law graduates seeking admission to the State Bar Council rolls: ₹600 to the State Bar Council and ₹150 to the Bar Council of India (₹100 and ₹25 respectively for SC/ST candidates).


Article 14, Constitution of India — guarantees equality before the law.


Article 19(1)(g), Constitution of India — protects the right to practise any profession, trade or occupation.



🧩 Factual Background
The petitioner, Gaurav Kumar, filed a writ petition under Article 32 challenging the practice of several State Bar Councils (SBCs) charging exorbitant enrolment fees—ranging between ₹10,000 and ₹50,000—far exceeding the statutory limits under Section 24(1)(f) of the Advocates Act, 1961.


SBCs justified the additional charges as contributions towards library funds, welfare schemes, administrative expenses, and other institutional costs.


The petitioner argued that these amounts were unauthorized and exclusionary, disproportionately burdening law graduates from economically weaker backgrounds.



⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether State Bar Councils can levy enrolment fees exceeding the limits prescribed in Section 24(1)(f) of the Advocates Act.


Whether miscellaneous charges—such as library or welfare fund contributions—can be made a mandatory precondition for enrolment to the State rolls.


Whether such excessive fee demands violate the fundamental rights under Articles 14 and 19(1)(g).



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court held that:
“No State Bar Council possesses authority to impose enrolment fees beyond what Parliament has prescribed under Section 24(1)(f). The legal profession must remain accessible to all; financial barriers contrary to statutory limits offend both equality and liberty.”
Accordingly, the Court struck down all enrolment fee structures that exceeded the statutory ceiling and prohibited the collection of ancillary charges as conditions for enrolment.

💡 Reasoning of the Court
Statutory Limitation (Advocates Act):


The Advocates Act expressly enumerates the permissible enrolment fee; any enhancement must emanate from legislative amendment, not administrative circulars.


SBCs, being statutory bodies, cannot expand their powers through self-regulation.


Violation of Article 14 — Equality & Inclusivity:


High enrolment fees create economic discrimination, restricting entry into the profession for less-privileged aspirants.


The Court emphasized that the Bar is an institution of service, not privilege; access must remain non-elitist.


Violation of Article 19(1)(g):


The right to practise law forms part of the constitutional guarantee under Article 19(1)(g).


Excessive or arbitrary fees constitute an unreasonable restriction, lacking legal authority under Article 19(6).


No Mandatory Miscellaneous Fees:


Contributions towards welfare or library funds may be encouraged but cannot be preconditions to enrolment.


The enrolment process must be confined strictly to statutory requisites under the Advocates Act and Rules.


Prospective Application:


The ruling operates prospectively: SBCs need not refund excess amounts already collected but must immediately adopt the prescribed statutory scale for future admissions.



✅ Decision / Directions
All State Bar Councils were directed to align enrolment fee structures with Section 24(1)(f).


SBCs may collect voluntary contributions for welfare funds but not as a condition precedent to enrolment.


The Bar Council of India (BCI) was tasked to issue uniform guidelines ensuring compliance nationwide.



🌟 Significance & Key Takeaways
Reinforces Parliamentary supremacy in regulating professional access through the Advocates Act.


Affirms that economic accessibility is integral to the right to practise law under Article 19(1)(g).


Curtails arbitrary fee imposition by State Bar Councils, promoting inclusivity within the legal profession.


Strengthens the principle that statutory bodies cannot exceed delegated authority.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
V. Sudeer v. Bar Council of India (1999) — clarified that the BCI and SBCs cannot create additional barriers inconsistent with the Advocates Act.


Indian Medical Association v. Union of India (2011) — affirmed that regulatory bodies cannot impose fees contrary to statutory prescription.


State of Maharashtra v. Indian Hotel and Restaurants Assn. (2013) — underscored proportionality of restrictions under Article 19(1)(g).


T.M.A. Pai Foundation v. State of Karnataka (2002) — linked affordability in professional access to equality principles.


Bar Council of India v. Bonnie Foi Law College (2023) — reaffirmed the statutory autonomy of BCI vis-à-vis State Councils.



⚖️ CS-24-24 | Gene Campaign v. Union of India (2024)
Citation: 2024 SCC OnLine SC 538 | Decided on: 27 May 2024
Bench: Justice B.V. Nagarathna and Justice Sanjay Karol

📘 Relevant Provisions
Article 21, Constitution of India – Right to life includes the right to a safe, healthy environment and access to safe food.


Article 48A – Directive Principle mandating protection and improvement of the environment.


Article 51A(g) – Fundamental duty of citizens to protect the natural environment.


Environment (Protection) Act, 1986, and 1989 Rules – Governing framework for the approval and environmental release of Genetically Modified (GM) organisms.


Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety, 2000 and Convention on Biological Diversity, 1992 – International environmental treaties emphasizing the precautionary principle.



🧩 Factual Background
The case arose from the Union Government’s decision on 25 October 2022, approving the environmental release of the genetically modified (GM) mustard hybrid “Dhara Mustard Hybrid-11 (DMH-11)”.


The petitioner, Gene Campaign, a non-governmental organization advocating for biodiversity and farmers’ rights, filed a writ petition under Article 32, contending that the approval violated citizens’ rights to a safe environment and health under Article 21.


It was argued that the Genetic Engineering Appraisal Committee (GEAC) granted approval without sufficient environmental assessment, stakeholder consultation, or independent peer review, contrary to the precautionary principle of environmental law.


The petition also questioned India’s compliance with its international obligations under the Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety and Convention on Biological Diversity.



⚖️ Issues Before the Court
Whether the Union Government’s 2022 approval for the environmental release of GM mustard (DMH-11) complied with the Environment (Protection) Act and constitutional guarantees under Article 21.


Whether the regulatory oversight of GM crops in India satisfies the constitutional requirement of transparency, precaution, and public participation.


Whether the Supreme Court should impose a moratorium on GM crop releases pending stronger biosafety regulation and scientific review.



🏛 Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court delivered a split verdict:
Justice B.V. Nagarathna’s Opinion (for caution and reform)
Held that the approval process was procedurally flawed — the Union Government failed to consult state authorities, independent scientists, and stakeholders, and the GEAC’s evaluation lacked transparency.


Directed that the GEAC must be reconstituted with experts in ecology, biodiversity, and public health.


Stressed that the precautionary principle is binding under Article 21, requiring the State to err on the side of environmental safety where scientific uncertainty persists.


Ordered that no commercial cultivation or release of DMH-11 should occur until further expert review is conducted.


Justice Sanjay Karol’s Opinion (for regulated continuation)
Held that the Union Government’s approval was within its policy and statutory powers, as GEAC had followed procedural safeguards.


Observed that judicial intervention must respect the executive’s policy prerogative in scientific and agricultural innovation.


Permitted controlled field trials of DMH-11 under close monitoring and periodic environmental impact assessments.


Directed the GEAC to conduct independent post-release biosafety studies and ensure public disclosure of all trial data.



💡 Reasoning of the Court
Constitutional Right to Environmental Safety:


Both Justices agreed that Article 21 encompasses the right to a safe and healthy environment, but diverged on whether the 2022 approval breached it.


Precautionary Principle:


Justice Nagarathna applied it strictly, emphasizing that uncertainty demands restraint; “once ecological harm occurs, it is irreversible.”


Justice Karol applied it flexibly, balancing precaution with scientific progress and national food security concerns.


Procedural Irregularities & Public Consultation:


Justice Nagarathna found deficiencies in public participation and transparency in GEAC’s evaluation.


Justice Karol held that existing institutional mechanisms sufficiently ensured scientific scrutiny.


International Environmental Commitments:


The Court reaffirmed India’s adherence to the Cartagena Protocol, which mandates biosafety risk assessment before GMO release.



✅ Decision / Directions
Due to the split verdict, the matter was referred to a larger Bench for authoritative adjudication.


Meanwhile, the Supreme Court directed that:


The GEAC conduct a comprehensive re-evaluation of DMH-11’s biosafety data.


All future GM approvals must include independent peer review, public consultation, and real-time disclosure of safety assessments.


The Union Government must ensure post-release environmental monitoring and submit compliance reports periodically.



🌿 Significance & Key Takeaways
First major Supreme Court split verdict on GM crop regulation in India.


Reiterates that the right to a healthy environment and food safety form part of Article 21’s substantive due process.


Clarifies that judicial review applies to executive actions on biotechnology when environmental or health impacts are uncertain.


Strengthens scientific accountability, transparency, and public involvement in GMO decision-making.


Balances technological advancement with constitutional environmentalism.



🔗 Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
Vellore Citizens’ Welfare Forum v. Union of India (1996) – Introduced the precautionary principle and polluter pays principle into Indian law.


A.P. Pollution Control Board v. Prof. M.V. Nayudu (1999) – Emphasized that decisions involving complex science must err on the side of caution.


Hanuman Laxman Aroskar v. Union of India (2020) – Stressed the importance of procedural integrity and stakeholder participation in environmental clearances.


Himachal Pradesh Bus-Stand Management Authority v. Central Empowered Committee (2021) – Reaffirmed judicial responsibility in enforcing environmental compliance.


M.C. Mehta v. Union of India (1987) – Expanded Article 21 to include environmental protection and ecological balance.


