⚖️ 
CS-24-25 | Goa Foundation v. State of Goa & Ors. (2024)
Citation: 2024 LiveLaw (SC) 61 | Decided on: 24 January 2024
Bench: Justice B.R. Gavai, Justice Aravind Kumar, and Justice Prashant Kumar Mishra

📘 
Relevant Provisions
Forest (Conservation) Act, 1980 (FCA) – Section 2: Restricts the use of forest land for non-forest purposes without prior approval of the Central Government.


Article 48A, Constitution of India – Directs the State to protect and improve the environment and safeguard forests.


Article 51A(g) – Fundamental duty of every citizen to protect the natural environment.


Article 21 – Recognizes the right to a clean and healthy environment as part of the right to life.



🧩 
Factual Background
The case arose from a long-standing dispute over the criteria for identifying and classifying “forests” in the State of Goa for the purpose of applying the Forest (Conservation) Act, 1980.


The National Green Tribunal (NGT) had earlier dismissed a plea filed by Goa Foundation, noting that the issue of defining “forest” was already being considered by the Supreme Court in the ongoing T.N. Godavarman Thirumulpad v. Union of India proceedings.


Goa Foundation, however, challenged the State’s 2016 criteria for identifying private forests, arguing that the criteria excluded areas of natural vegetation with lower canopy density (0.1–0.4) and thus allowed large-scale deforestation and mining under the guise of non-forest classification.


The State of Goa maintained that its criteria were consistent with ecological parameters recognized in earlier judicial and expert committee reports.



⚖️ 
Issues Before the Court
Whether areas with natural vegetation having tree canopy density between 0.1 to 0.4 should be classified as “forest” under the Forest (Conservation) Act, 1980.


Whether the criteria for identification of forests in Goa were arbitrary or contrary to directions in T.N. Godavarman and subsequent environmental jurisprudence.



🏛 
Judgment / Ratio Decidendi
The Supreme Court upheld the criteria adopted by the State of Goa, holding that they were scientifically sound, reasonable, and consistent with existing precedents and policies.
“The existing criteria based on forest tree composition, contiguity of forest land, minimum area of five hectares, and a canopy density not less than 0.4 are adequate and valid for the purpose of identifying forests in Goa.”
The Court thus affirmed the NGT’s order, finding no reason to modify or expand the criteria to include areas with canopy density below 0.4.

💡 
Reasoning of the Court
Finality of Criteria:


The issue of forest identification in Goa had reached finality through prior orders in the Godavarman case.


The criteria — (a) forest tree composition, (b) contiguity, (c) minimum area of 5 hectares, and (d) canopy density ≥ 0.4 — were scientifically validated and administratively implementable.


Ecological Consistency:


The Court observed that defining forests too broadly to include all vegetated areas (e.g., canopy density of 0.1–0.4) would lead to impracticable enforcement and hinder legitimate land use and development under existing environmental safeguards.


Precedential Authority:


Referred to T.N. Godavarman Thirumulpad v. Union of India (1997), which expanded the definition of forest to include all statutorily recognized forests, whether reserved or otherwise.


Reiterated Lafarge Umiam Mining Pvt. Ltd. v. Union of India (2011), where the Court directed all States to formulate uniform, scientifically informed forest identification criteria before granting clearances.


Balance Between Conservation and Governance:


The Court emphasized that forest conservation policy must balance ecological preservation with rational administrative boundaries, ensuring both environmental and socio-economic sustainability.



✅ 
Decision / Directions
The Supreme Court upheld the State’s forest identification criteria as valid.


Declared that no modification was required, and that canopy density of 0.4 remains the appropriate threshold for defining forest areas under the FCA.


Affirmed that forest identification and demarcation must follow the principles evolved in T.N. Godavarman and subsequent monitoring processes by the Central Empowered Committee (CEC).



🌿 
Significance & Key Takeaways
Reaffirms the scientific approach to forest identification and the importance of canopy density in ecological classification.


Ensures legal certainty and administrative consistency in forest management within the Goa region.


Clarifies that environmental protection under Article 21 and Article 48A must operate within the bounds of scientific criteria and judicially recognized standards.


Reinforces the continuing jurisdictional relevance of the Godavarman series in all forest-related matters.



🔗 
Referred / Related Cases and Their Significance
T.N. Godavarman Thirumulpad v. Union of India (1997) – Expanded the definition of “forest” under Section 2 of the FCA and established continuous judicial monitoring of forest matters.


Lafarge Umiam Mining Pvt. Ltd. v. Union of India (2011) – Directed States to prepare comprehensive guidelines for forest identification and clearance.


M.C. Mehta v. Union of India (1987) – Recognized environmental protection as part of the right to life under Article 21.


Hanuman Laxman Aroskar v. Union of India (2020) – Reaffirmed the need for procedural rigor in environmental clearances.



⚖️ CS-24-26 | Government of NCT of Delhi v. Office of Lieutenant Governor of Delhi (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 578 | Decided on: 5 August 2024
Bench: Chief Justice (Dr.) D.Y. Chandrachud, Justice P.S. Narasimha, Justice J.B. Pardiwala

🧭 Relevant Provisions
Article 239AA(4), Constitution of India – Defines the powers of the Lieutenant Governor (LG) and Council of Ministers of the NCT of Delhi.


Article 239AA(7) – Empowers Parliament to make laws to give effect to the provisions of Article 239AA.


Section 3(3)(b)(i), Delhi Municipal Corporation Act, 1957 (DMC Act) – Authorises the LG to nominate ten persons to the Municipal Corporation of Delhi (MCD).


Entry 5, List II (State List) – Local government, including municipalities.



🧩 Background of the Case
The Municipal Corporation of Delhi (MCD) comprises 250 elected councillors and 10 nominated members.


Under Section 3(3)(b)(i) of the DMC Act, the Lieutenant Governor nominates ten persons with special knowledge in municipal administration.


After the 2022 MCD elections, where the Aam Aadmi Party won a majority, the LG nominated ten members without consulting the Delhi Government.


The Government of NCT of Delhi (GNCTD) filed a writ petition under Article 32, arguing that the LG was bound by the aid and advice of the Council of Ministers when making such nominations.



⚖️ Legal Issue
Whether the Lieutenant Governor is bound by the aid and advice of the Delhi Government’s Council of Ministers when nominating members to the MCD under Section 3(3)(b)(i) of the DMC Act, 1957.

🧠 Petitioner’s Arguments (Delhi Government)
The Delhi Government argued that Article 239AA(4) makes the LG bound by the aid and advice of the elected Council of Ministers in all matters where the Delhi Legislative Assembly can make laws.


Since the MCD deals with “local government” under Entry 5 of List II, the LG must act on ministerial advice.


Unilateral nominations by the LG violate representative democracy, constitutional morality, and the 2018 Constitution Bench ruling in NCT of Delhi v. Union of India (2018).



⚖️ Respondent’s Arguments (Union of India / LG)
The DMC Act is a law enacted by Parliament, and Article 239AA(4) allows the LG to act in his discretion where a law so requires.


Since Section 3(3)(b)(i) specifically empowers the LG to nominate members, it creates a statutory exception to the general rule of aid and advice.


The LG’s nominations are not administrative actions, but statutory duties under the DMC Act — thus, they fall outside ministerial control.



🏛️ 
Judgment (Authored by Justice P.S. Narasimha)
The Supreme Court dismissed the Delhi Government’s plea and held that:
The LG is not bound by the aid and advice of the Council of Ministers when nominating ten members to the MCD under Section 3(3)(b)(i) of the DMC Act.


The DMC Act is a law enacted by Parliament under Article 239AA(7) and Entry 5 of List II, governing local government functions.


Once Parliament enacts a law on a matter within the legislative competence of Delhi, the executive power of the Delhi Government becomes subject to that law (¶15, ¶22).


Article 239AA(4) expressly provides an exception allowing the LG to act in his discretion “when required by or under any law.”


Thus, since the DMC Act authorizes the LG directly, he acts in his statutory discretion, not on ministerial advice.



🧩 
Key Reasoning
Distinction from the 2018 NCT Case:

 The Court reaffirmed that while the LG is generally bound by the Council of Ministers’ advice, this case is distinguishable because the DMC Act creates a specific statutory duty for the LG to nominate members.


Effect of Parliamentary Law:

 Once Parliament legislates on a matter (here, municipal administration), the Delhi Government’s authority under Article 239AA must yield to that law’s provisions.


Different Status from Governors:

 The LG’s powers differ from those of a State Governor. The Governor’s discretion is constitutional, while the LG’s discretion can also arise from a statute (¶21, ¶37).



📚 
Ratio Decidendi
The Lieutenant Governor of Delhi is not bound by the aid and advice of the Council of Ministers when performing a statutory function under a law enacted by Parliament, such as nominating members under Section 3(3)(b)(i) of the DMC Act.

🔗 
Referred / Related Cases
State (NCT of Delhi) v. Union of India (2018 INSC 577) – LG must ordinarily act on the aid and advice of the Council of Ministers.


Government of NCT of Delhi v. Union of India (2023 INSC 517) – Executive control over “services” remains with the Delhi Government except for reserved subjects.


Shamsher Singh v. State of Punjab (1974) – Limits of discretionary powers of constitutional heads.


S.R. Bommai v. Union of India (1994) – Federalism as a basic structure of the Constitution.



🧾 
Significance
Clarifies the constitutional relationship between the LG and the Delhi Government.


Distinguishes between constitutional discretion (under Article 163) and statutory discretion (under Article 239AA(4)).


Strengthens the doctrine of legislative supremacy of Parliament over the NCT of Delhi.


Balances representative democracy with administrative practicality in Union Territories.



🏁 
Conclusion
The Supreme Court upheld the Lieutenant Governor’s power of nomination under the DMC Act, ruling that it is a statutory function falling within the discretionary exception under Article 239AA(4).
The decision reinforces Parliament’s supremacy in matters relating to Union Territories, even where there is an elected government, reaffirming the unique federal structure envisaged for Delhi.

⚖️ CS-24-27 | High Court Bar Association, Allahabad v. State of Uttar Pradesh (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 150 | Decided on: 29 February 2024
Bench: Chief Justice (Dr.) D.Y. Chandrachud, Justice Abhay S. Oka, Justice J.B. Pardiwala, Justice Pankaj Mithal, and Justice Manoj Misra

🧭 
Relevant Provisions
Article 142 – Power of the Supreme Court to do “complete justice.”


Article 226 – Power of High Courts to issue writs.


Article 227 – Power of superintendence of High Courts over subordinate courts.


Principles of Natural Justice – Right to fair hearing before any adverse judicial order.



🧩 
Background
The case arose from the Supreme Court’s 2018 judgment in Asian Resurfacing of Road Agency v. Central Bureau of Investigation (2018 INSC 282), where a three-judge bench directed that:
Any stay order passed by a High Court in civil or criminal matters would automatically expire after six months unless extended by a reasoned order.


High Courts should decide all such matters within six months on a day-to-day basis.


On 1 December 2023, a later bench of the Supreme Court (CJI Chandrachud, JJ. Pardiwala, and Misra) referred the correctness of these directions to a Constitution Bench, expressing doubts about whether Asian Resurfacing’s blanket directions were constitutionally valid.

⚖️ 
Questions Before the Court
Can the Supreme Court direct that all interim orders of High Courts automatically lapse after a fixed period, such as six months?


Can the Supreme Court, under Article 142, direct all High Courts to dispose of pending cases within a fixed timeframe?



⚖️ 
Judgment
The five-judge Constitution Bench unanimously overruled parts of the 2018 Asian Resurfacing judgment, holding that the automatic expiry of interim orders and mandatory time-bound hearings are impermissible and beyond the scope of Article 142.
Judgment authored by: Justice Abhay S. Oka.


Concurring opinion: Justice Pankaj Mithal.



🧠 
Key Findings and Legal Reasoning
1️⃣ 
Automatic expiration of stay orders violates natural justice
Interim orders cannot lapse automatically without giving the affected party a right to be heard.


The 2018 directions ignored the merits and context of each case and punished litigants for delays beyond their control.


Justice Mithal added that an interim stay can only end if the opposite side files an application and the court passes a reasoned order following due process.


🏛️ “Automatic expiry of judicial orders without hearing violates fundamental fairness and procedural due process.”

2️⃣ 
Limits on Article 142 powers
The Supreme Court’s power under Article 142 is not unlimited; it must be exercised only to do complete justice between the parties before it, not to create general procedural mandates for all courts.


Article 142 cannot be used to:


Nullify existing judicial orders validly passed by High Courts.


Affect substantive rights of litigants who were not parties to the original proceedings.


Override established statutory or constitutional frameworks.


🏛️ “Article 142 does not authorise judicial legislation or universal directions which alter rights of non-parties.”

3️⃣ 
High Courts are not subordinate to the Supreme Court
The Court reaffirmed that High Courts are constitutional courts, not “judicially subordinate” to the Supreme Court.


Under Article 227, High Courts have supervisory jurisdiction over subordinate courts, including the power to grant or vacate interim stays.


Imposing blanket restrictions or deadlines on High Court proceedings encroaches upon judicial independence.



4️⃣ 
Time-bound directions to High Courts only in exceptional cases
Directions prescribing fixed timeframes for disposal of cases may only be issued in exceptional categories of cases, where delay undermines justice.


Otherwise, such orders amount to judicial legislation, which is constitutionally impermissible.


Each High Court is best suited to manage its own docket and determine case priorities.



📚 
Ratio Decidendi
An interim stay granted by a High Court cannot automatically expire after any fixed period. The Supreme Court cannot, under Article 142, issue blanket directions to subordinate constitutional courts imposing deadlines or limiting their jurisdiction. Each High Court retains discretion to manage its cases consistent with natural justice and judicial independence.

