1️⃣ 
No exception for “consensual acts” under the POCSO Act
The Supreme Court firmly held that the POCSO Act recognizes no concept of “non-exploitative sexual acts” with minors.


Any sexual act with a person below 18 years is statutorily rape, regardless of the alleged “consent” or romantic nature of the relationship.


The High Court’s reference to “older adolescents” and its sociological commentary were found wholly irrelevant and contrary to legislative intent.


The Court reiterated that courts cannot override statutory mandates through equitable or moral reasoning (¶16–19).


2️⃣ 
Improper use of discretionary powers
The bench criticized the High Court’s exercise of powers under Article 226 and Section 482 Cr.P.C., noting that serious offences like rape cannot be quashed even if the parties later reconcile or marry.


Judicial discretion must align with the statute; it cannot nullify express provisions of penal law (¶21–23.1).


The purpose of the POCSO Act is to protect children from sexual exploitation, in harmony with India’s obligations under the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child (1992).


3️⃣ 
Obligations of the State under the JJ Act
The Court observed that the State Government failed to provide rehabilitation and protection to the victim, as mandated under Section 2(14) JJ Act.


It directed the constitution of a committee including a clinical psychologist and a social scientist to assist the victim in rehabilitation.


The Child Welfare Committees (CWCs) must ensure care, counselling, and reintegration for victims of sexual offences (¶28–29).


4️⃣ 
Judicial restraint and judgment writing
The Supreme Court censured the High Court’s personal moral observations on teenage sexuality, calling them unwarranted and paternalistic.


Judicial pronouncements must be objective, concise, and reasoned, avoiding personal commentary or policy advice (¶13–17).



🧾 
Judgment (Held)
The Supreme Court restored the conviction of the accused under Section 6 POCSO Act and Sections 376(2)(n) & 376(3) IPC for rape of a minor.


The acquittal under Sections 363 and 366 IPC (kidnapping) was upheld as the victim had voluntarily left home.


The Court reaffirmed that “consensual” relations with a minor are legally rape under POCSO and IPC.


The judgment was authored by Justice Abhay S. Oka.



⚖️ 
Ratio Decidendi
Consent is immaterial under POCSO — any sexual act with a person below 18 is an offence, even in “romantic” contexts.


High Courts cannot invoke inherent or writ powers to nullify valid convictions for serious crimes.


Judicial commentary must be confined to findings of fact and law, not sociological advice.


The State bears affirmative duties to rehabilitate and protect child victims under the Juvenile Justice Act.



📚 
Significance
Reinforces that sexual autonomy under 18 has no legal recognition under Indian criminal law.


Strengthens judicial discipline in judgment writing, rejecting subjective or moral reasoning.


Promotes victim rehabilitation through psychological and institutional support mechanisms.


Clarifies limits of Article 226 and Section 482 in criminal proceedings involving heinous offences.



🔗 
Key Precedents Referred
State of M.P. v. Laxmi Narayan (2019) – High Courts cannot quash convictions for serious offences based on compromise.


Independent Thought v. Union of India (2017) – Marital rape exception invalid for minors; consent of under-18 immaterial.


Subrata Chattoraj v. Union of India (2014) – Scope of High Court’s inherent powers.


Nipun Saxena v. Union of India (2019) – Privacy and dignity of sexual assault victims are integral to Article 21.



💬 
In Essence
The Supreme Court’s decision in In Re: Right to Privacy of Adolescents (2024) is a strong affirmation that:
Statutory protection of minors under POCSO cannot be diluted through notions of romantic consent;


Judicial discretion must remain disciplined, not moralistic; and


Victims’ welfare and rehabilitation are a constitutional and statutory responsibility of the State.


