Background
The Indian Medical Association (IMA) filed a writ petition against Patanjali Ayurved Ltd., alleging repeated dissemination of misleading and disparaging advertisements that falsely claimed allopathy and modern medicine were inferior to Ayurvedic treatments.
The case expanded beyond Patanjali’s conduct to examine misleading advertisements across the healthcare, food, and consumer goods sectors, focusing on regulatory failures and public accountability.

⚖️ 
Key Issues
Whether misleading advertisements violate the consumer’s right to health and informed choice under Article 21.


What are the responsibilities of manufacturers, advertisers, and endorsers in ensuring truthful, non-deceptive claims?


Whether the existing regulatory and self-regulatory mechanisms are sufficient to prevent misleading advertisements.


What should be the role of statutory bodies and ministries (AYUSH, FSSAI, I&B) in monitoring and enforcing advertising standards.



🧠 Arguments
🏛️ Petitioner (IMA)
Claimed misleading advertisements were endangering public health and exploiting consumer ignorance.


Celebrities and influencers endorsed untested or false health products without due diligence, violating the 2022 Guidelines.


Statutory regulators like FSSAI and the Ministry of AYUSH failed to act suo motu or address complaints effectively.


Misleading health claims violated Article 21, as the right to life includes the right to safe, informed healthcare choices.


Sought judicial intervention for a centralized monitoring mechanism and mandatory self-declaration of all ads.


⚖️ Respondent (Union of India, Ministry of AYUSH, Patanjali, et al.)
Contended that existing laws (Drugs & Magic Remedies Act, FSSAI Act, Consumer Protection Act) already provided adequate safeguards.


Claimed that self-regulation through industry bodies and advertising councils was sufficient.


Stated that the AYUSH sector required policy support, not over-regulation, to avoid stifling traditional medicine and economic growth.


Asserted ongoing reform efforts, including amendments to Rule 170 of the Drugs and Cosmetics Rules, 1945, to curb false claims.


Emphasized that advertisers should retain autonomy so long as they comply with legal frameworks.



🧾 
Judgment
The Supreme Court delivered a landmark ruling reinforcing public health, transparency, and consumer protection in advertising.
1️⃣ 
Right to Health under Article 21
The Court held that the right to health includes the right to be informed about the quality, composition, and effects of products consumed.


Misleading advertisements violate Article 21, as they deprive consumers of informed consent and safety.


2️⃣ 
Self-Declaration Requirement
Directed that before any advertisement is published, aired, or displayed, advertisers must submit a self-declaration certificate affirming compliance with all applicable laws.


This declaration must be uploaded on designated government portals:


Broadcast Seva Portal (for electronic media)


Press Council of India Portal (for print media).


This mechanism became operational on 18 June 2024, ensuring transparency and traceability.


3️⃣ 
Regulatory Accountability
Directed the Ministry of Information & Broadcasting (I&B) and the Ministry of AYUSH to coordinate for strict implementation.


Ordered enhanced monitoring by FSSAI and Central Consumer Protection Authority (CCPA) to verify claims in health-related ads.


4️⃣ 
Contempt Proceedings
Noting Patanjali’s continued dissemination of misleading claims despite earlier undertakings, the Court initiated contempt proceedings against:


Patanjali Ayurved Ltd.


Acharya Balkrishna (MD)


Baba Ramdev (Co-founder)


5️⃣ 
Stay on Omission of Rule 170
The Court stayed the Central Government’s decision to delete Rule 170 of the Drugs and Cosmetics Rules, 1945, which regulates misleading advertisements for Ayurvedic, Siddha, and Unani medicines.



📘 
Ratio Decidendi
Consumer’s right to health under Article 21 includes the right to truthful commercial information.


Advertisements are not absolute expressions under Article 19(1)(a); they are subject to reasonable restrictions under Article 19(2).


Manufacturers, endorsers, and advertising agencies owe a duty of care to ensure scientific accuracy and compliance with regulatory codes.


Misleading advertisements in health and food sectors directly infringe the fundamental right to life and dignity.


The state has a positive constitutional obligation to protect citizens from deceptive commercial practices.



🧩 
Important Precedents Referred
Case
Principle
Tata Press Ltd. v. Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Ltd. (1995)
Commercial speech is protected under Article 19(1)(a) but subject to reasonable restrictions.
Consumer Education & Research Centre v. Union of India (1995)
Right to health is integral to Article 21.
Hamdard Dawakhana v. Union of India (1960)
Misleading advertisements are not protected under Article 19(1)(a).
Common Cause v. Union of India (2018)
Public health is a matter of constitutional importance; state must prevent exploitation.


⚖️ 
Significance
Establishes constitutional recognition of consumers’ right to be informed about health and food products.


Creates a digital compliance ecosystem for advertisements through self-declaration portals.


Reinforces corporate accountability and endorsers’ liability.


Strengthens judicial oversight over deceptive medical and nutritional claims.


Balances AYUSH sector promotion with public safety obligations.



📌 In Essence
The Supreme Court in IMA v. Union of India (2024) expanded Article 21 to include the consumer’s right to accurate product information, making misleading health-related advertisements a violation of fundamental rights.
It mandated mandatory self-declarations, enhanced regulatory vigilance, and warned advertisers and endorsers that dishonest promotions will attract both statutory and contempt consequences.


📘 CS-24-34 | Javed Ahmad Hajam v. State of Maharashtra (2024)
📅 Citation: 2024 INSC 187 (7 March 2024)
⚖️ Bench: Justice Abhay S. Oka and Justice Ujjal Bhuyan

⚖️ Legal Provisions Involved
Section 153A, Indian Penal Code, 1860 – Punishment for promoting enmity between different groups on grounds of religion, race, place of birth, residence, language, etc.


Article 19(1)(a), Constitution of India – Freedom of speech and expression.


Article 19(2), Constitution of India – Permits reasonable restrictions on free speech in the interest of public order, morality, and sovereignty of India.



🧾 
Background
The appellant, a professor from Jammu & Kashmir teaching in Maharashtra, posted WhatsApp statuses criticising the abrogation of Article 370 and extending greetings to Pakistan on its Independence Day. His messages were:
“August 5 – Black Day Jammu & Kashmir”


“14th August – Happy Independence Day Pakistan”


“Article 370 was abrogated, we are not happy.”


An FIR was lodged under Section 153A IPC, alleging that these statements promoted disharmony and enmity among groups. The Bombay High Court refused to quash the FIR, following which the appellant approached the Supreme Court.

❓ 
Issues
Whether the WhatsApp status messages posted by the appellant constitute an offence under Section 153A of the Indian Penal Code, 1860.


What is the correct threshold for applying Section 153A IPC — does it require proof of deliberate and malicious intent to incite enmity between groups?


Whether expressions of dissent or goodwill toward another nation can be criminalised under Article 19(2) restrictions.



🧑‍⚖️ 
Decision
The Supreme Court quashed the FIR, holding that the appellant’s conduct did not meet the legal threshold of Section 153A IPC. His posts were mere expressions of political dissent, protected under Article 19(1)(a). The Court reaffirmed that criticism of government policies cannot be construed as promoting enmity or hatred.

💡 
Reasoning
Absence of Mens Rea: The Court ruled that intent to incite enmity or hatred is an essential ingredient under Section 153A. The appellant’s messages lacked any deliberate or malicious motive.


Freedom to Dissent: Peaceful criticism of governmental action, such as opposing the abrogation of Article 370, is a constitutionally protected right.


Reasonable Person Test: The impact of speech must be judged by the standard of a reasonable person, not by hypersensitive reactions of individuals intolerant to opposing views.


Goodwill Expression: Extending greetings to another country’s citizens, such as Pakistan, does not amount to disloyalty or sedition. It is a benign expression of goodwill that cannot attract criminal liability.



⚖️ 
Ratio Decidendi
For an offence under Section 153A IPC, the prosecution must prove:
The existence of a deliberate and malicious intent to promote enmity; and


A direct nexus between the words used and the likelihood of public disorder.

 Since neither element was satisfied, the FIR was unsustainable in law.



🧠 
Key Observations
“Every criticism of State action cannot be equated with disloyalty or hatred.”


“The Constitution protects not only agreeable speech but also the right to disagree.”


“Democracy thrives on dissent — criminalising it would destroy its foundation.”


“Criminal law must not become a weapon to silence political or ideological opposition.”



⚖️ 
Significance
The judgment reaffirms that peaceful dissent is not a crime. It narrows the application of Section 153A IPC to genuine cases involving malicious intent to provoke communal disharmony. It upholds the principle that free political expression lies at the heart of India’s constitutional democracy.

📚 
Important Precedents Referred
Shreya Singhal v. Union of India (2015): Struck down Section 66A IT Act; emphasised protection of online dissent.


Balwant Singh v. State of Punjab (1995): Held that slogans like “Khalistan Zindabad” without violence do not amount to sedition or hate speech.


Amish Devgan v. Union of India (2020): Clarified that intent and context are crucial in determining hate speech.


Maneka Gandhi v. Union of India (1978): Interpreted personal liberty and free speech as interdependent constitutional guarantees.



🏛️ 
Conclusion
The Supreme Court quashed the FIR against Professor Javed Ahmad Hajam, holding that his posts merely reflected political opinion and dissent. The judgment is a reaffirmation that democracy cannot exist without the right to disagree and that Section 153A IPC cannot be stretched to penalise lawful criticism or harmless expressions of belief.
🕊️ “In a democracy, the right to dissent is not sedition — it is the soul of liberty.”
