📘 CS-24-35 | Just Rights for Children Alliance v. S. Harish (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 716 (23 September 2024)
Bench: Chief Justice Dr. D.Y. Chandrachud and Justice J.B. Pardiwala

⚖️ 
Background
This case addressed whether merely viewing or possessing Child Sexual Exploitation and Abuse Material (CESAM)—commonly known as child pornography—constitutes a criminal offence under Indian law. The respondent, S. Harish, was accused of downloading and storing CESAM on his phone. The Madras High Court had quashed the criminal proceedings, holding that mere viewing without sharing or publishing such material was not punishable. The petitioner, an NGO working to combat child exploitation, appealed to the Supreme Court.

🧩 
Key Legal Questions
1️⃣ Whether viewing CESAM amounts to an offence under Section 15(1) of the Protection of Children from Sexual Offences Act, 2012 (POCSO) and Section 67B of the Information Technology Act, 2000.
2️⃣ What is the scope of “possession” under Section 15(1) of the POCSO Act — does it include temporary or constructive possession?
3️⃣ Whether the statutory presumption of culpable mental state under Section 30 of the POCSO Act can be invoked even at the quashing stage.

📜 
Relevant Legal Provisions
Section 15(1), POCSO Act: Punishes possession or storage of CESAM, and failure to delete, destroy, or report it.


Section 30, POCSO Act: Presumes a culpable mental state unless proved otherwise.


Section 67B, IT Act: Penalises creation, transmission, or viewing of sexually explicit material involving children.


Articles 15(3) and 39(e)-(f) of the Constitution: Direct the State to protect children from exploitation and abuse.



📂 
Facts of the Case
Police found CESAM files on the respondent’s phone following a digital forensic examination.


He admitted to watching pornography during college years, and two videos containing CESAM were retrieved.


The initial charge under Section 14(1) POCSO (use of children for pornography) was dropped, replaced by Section 15(1) for possession and failure to delete CESAM.


The Madras High Court quashed the proceedings, holding that mere viewing without sharing does not constitute an offence.


NGOs appealed, arguing that the High Court’s interpretation weakened the deterrence against child exploitation.



⚖️ 
Decision of the Supreme Court
The Supreme Court set aside the Madras High Court’s judgment and restored the criminal proceedings, ruling that:
Mere viewing or possession of CESAM is punishable under Section 15(1) POCSO if the material is not deleted or reported.


The act of viewing CESAM creates constructive possession and contributes to the demand chain of exploitation.


The presumption of culpable intent under Section 30 POCSO applies even at the quashing stage, ensuring the statutory intent of strict protection is upheld.


The expression “child pornography” must be replaced with “Child Sexual Exploitation and Abuse Material (CESAM),” which reflects the gravity and exploitative nature of the offence.



🧠 
Court’s Reasoning
🔹 1. Broad Interpretation of Possession:
The Court held that “possession” includes both actual and constructive control—viewing or streaming CESAM online constitutes possession if the individual has control over the device or account used.
🔹 2. Inchoate Crime Doctrine:
The Court classified the offence as an inchoate crime—acts preparatory to exploitation that facilitate the continuation of a harmful cycle of abuse.
🔹 3. Presumption of Intent (Section 30 POCSO):
Given the secretive nature of such offences, the law presumes a guilty intention once possession is established. This presumption can be rebutted at trial, not at the quashing stage.
🔹 4. Role of Intermediaries:
Online platforms cannot claim immunity under Section 79 IT Act unless they both remove the content and report it to the authorities.
🔹 5. Terminology Reform:
The Court directed the Union Government to replace the term “child pornography” with “CESAM” via amendment or ordinance to better capture the exploitative nature of the act.

🧾 
Judgment Summary
The Court revived the prosecution of S. Harish.


Viewing = Possession = Punishable under Section 15(1).


High Courts must apply the statutory presumption even during quashing.


The Union Government was directed to enable online reporting mechanisms for CESAM under the POCSO Act.



🔗 
Referred / Related Cases & Their Significance
1️⃣ Independent Thought v. Union of India (2017): Reinforced child-centric interpretation of POCSO provisions.
2️⃣ Attorney General for India v. Satish (2021): Reaffirmed liberal and protective interpretation of child abuse laws.
3️⃣ Nupur Ghatge v. State of Madhya Pradesh (2020): Clarified scope of Section 67B IT Act in penalising viewing or transmission of CESAM.

💡 
Significance
This judgment redefines the legal approach to child sexual exploitation online. It bridges the gap between technological conduct (viewing/streaming) and physical possession, strengthens prosecutorial mechanisms under POCSO, and upholds India’s constitutional commitment to protect children from all forms of abuse.
⚖️ “Viewing the suffering of a child for gratification is not passive; it is participation.” — Supreme Court of India

📘 CS-24-36 | Jyoti Devi v. Suket Hospital & Ors. (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 492 (Bench: Justice Sanjay Karol and Justice Aravind Kumar)

⚖️ 
Background
This case concerns a medical negligence claim filed by Jyoti Devi, a patient who endured prolonged pain after an appendectomy due to a surgical needle left inside her abdomen. The Supreme Court examined not only the liability of the hospital but also the application of the “Eggshell Skull Rule” and the principle of just and fair compensation under the Consumer Protection Act, 1986.
The appellant sought enhancement of compensation, alleging that the lower fora had undervalued her suffering and medical expenses. The Supreme Court restored the higher compensation originally granted by the District Forum.

🧩 
Key Legal Questions
1️⃣ Whether the Eggshell Skull Rule applied in determining compensation in this case of medical negligence.
2️⃣ Whether the compensation awarded by the consumer forums was just, fair, and proportionate to the degree of injury and suffering caused by the hospital’s negligence.

📜 
Relevant Legal Framework
Section 12, Consumer Protection Act, 1986 — Enables consumers to file complaints for deficiency in medical service.


Eggshell Skull Rule (Common Law Doctrine): A defendant must “take the victim as they find them” and remains liable even if the plaintiff’s pre-existing vulnerability exacerbates the injury.


Principle of Restitutio in Integrum: Compensation must restore the injured party, as far as money can, to the position they would have been in had the injury not occurred.



📂 
Facts of the Case
Jyoti Devi underwent an appendicitis surgery at Suket Hospital in Himachal Pradesh.


Post-surgery, she continued to experience acute abdominal pain for nearly four years.


Multiple consultations and treatments failed to identify the cause of pain.


Later, at PGIMER, Chandigarh, it was discovered that a 2.5 cm surgical needle had been left inside her abdomen.


A second surgery was performed to remove the foreign object.


She filed a complaint alleging gross medical negligence and sought ₹19,80,000 in compensation.


Consumer Forum History:
🏛️ District Forum: Awarded ₹5,00,000 compensation.


⚖️ State Commission: Reduced to ₹1,00,000.


🏛️ National Commission: Enhanced to ₹2,00,000, invoking the Eggshell Skull Rule.


⚖️ Supreme Court: Restored the District Forum’s award of ₹5,00,000 and clarified the correct application of the rule.



⚖️ 
Judgment
The Supreme Court allowed the appeal, restoring the District Forum’s award of ₹5,00,000 and rejecting the reasoning of the SCDRC and NCDRC.
The Court held that the Eggshell Skull Rule was misapplied, as there was no evidence of any pre-existing vulnerability in the appellant.


The presence of a foreign surgical object inside a patient’s body is prima facie proof of negligence, and liability arises irrespective of subjective conditions.


The Court reiterated that compensation in medical negligence must be fair, reasonable, and based on restorative justice principles.



🧠 
Court’s Reasoning
🔹 1. Proof of Negligence:
Leaving a foreign object inside the patient’s body after surgery constitutes res ipsa loquitur — the act speaks for itself — and establishes negligence without requiring additional proof.
🔹 2. Limits of the Eggshell Skull Rule:
The doctrine applies only where the victim had a known pre-existing vulnerability that worsened the injury. Since no such evidence existed in this case, the Court held that the principle was wrongly invoked by the NCDRC.
🔹 3. Fair and Adequate Compensation:
The Supreme Court emphasized that consumer fora must ensure compensation reflects both physical pain and mental suffering, applying the principle of restitutio in integrum. Reduction of compensation without valid reasoning violates this standard.
🔹 4. Institutional Responsibility:
Hospitals are under a non-delegable duty of care to ensure post-operative checks and proper accounting of surgical instruments, irrespective of the attending doctor’s personal fault.

🧾 
Final Holding
Negligence Proven: The hospital was found guilty of a clear breach of duty.


Compensation Restored: ₹5,00,000 reinstated as awarded by the District Forum.


Clarification: The Eggshell Skull Rule applies narrowly and cannot justify arbitrary compensation reductions.



🔗 
Referred / Related Cases
1️⃣ Sarla Verma v. DTC (2009) 6 SCC 121 – Established principles for fair and uniform computation of compensation.
2️⃣ N. Chandrababu Naidu v. Union of India (2023) – Referred for delineating liability in cases involving multiple medical institutions.
3️⃣ Jacob Mathew v. State of Punjab (2005) 6 SCC 1 – Defined the standard of medical negligence as failure to exercise reasonable skill expected of a competent professional.
4️⃣ Indian Medical Association v. V.P. Shantha (1995) 6 SCC 651 – Brought medical services within the ambit of the Consumer Protection Act.
5️⃣ Spring Meadows Hospital v. Harjol Ahluwalia (1998) 4 SCC 39 – Imposed vicarious liability on hospitals for staff negligence.

💡 
Significance
This judgment reinforces patient safety and the principle of accountability in healthcare. It draws a fine line between ordinary negligence and gross negligence, while clarifying that compensation must neither be excessive nor symbolic — but just, reasoned, and restorative.
⚖️ “The measure of compensation in negligence is not generosity, but justice.”

