📘 CS-24-37 | Kolkata Municipal Corporation & Anr. v. Bimal Kumar Shah & Ors. (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 544 (26 July 2024)
Bench: Justice P.S. Narasimha and Justice Aravind Kumar

⚖️ 
Background
This case is a significant pronouncement on the limits of municipal authority, due process in property acquisition, and the scope of Article 300A of the Constitution, which protects an individual’s right to property.
The dispute arose when the Kolkata Municipal Corporation (KMC) sought to forcibly acquire private property for a public purpose—ostensibly to construct a park—without following the statutory procedure under the Kolkata Municipal Corporation Act, 1980.
The respondent, Bimal Kumar Shah, alleged that his property was unlawfully taken over, and his ownership was replaced with that of the corporation in the official land records. Both the trial court and the High Court ruled against the Corporation, leading to an appeal before the Supreme Court.

🧩 
Key Legal Issues
1️⃣ Whether the Kolkata Municipal Corporation can acquire private land under Section 352 of the KMC Act, 1980 without following due procedure.
2️⃣ Whether the unauthorised acquisition and alteration of ownership records violates Article 300A of the Constitution, which mandates that deprivation of property must be “by authority of law.”

📜 
Relevant Legal Provisions
Article 300A, Constitution of India — “No person shall be deprived of his property save by authority of law.”


Section 352, Kolkata Municipal Corporation Act, 1980 — Power of the Municipal Commissioner to acquire land for public purposes.


Section 537, KMC Act, 1980 — Procedure to be followed when immovable property cannot be acquired by agreement, requiring prior sanction of the State Government.



📂 
Facts of the Case
The Kolkata Municipal Corporation attempted to take possession of the respondent’s property under Section 352 of the KMC Act, claiming it was needed for a public park.


The Corporation deleted the respondent’s name as owner from official municipal records and substituted its own name.


The respondent filed a writ petition before the Calcutta High Court, seeking a stay on the acquisition and restoration of his ownership records.


The trial court held that Section 352 does not confer compulsory acquisition powers, which must follow procedures under Section 537.


The High Court affirmed this finding, directing that the respondent’s ownership be restored.


The Corporation appealed to the Supreme Court, asserting that its actions were in accordance with the law.



⚖️ 
Arguments
Petitioner (Kolkata Municipal Corporation):
Claimed statutory authority under Section 352 to acquire property for public purposes such as constructing parks or public utilities.


Contended that the High Court erred in holding that Section 537 was the exclusive provision for acquisition.


Cited State of Kerala v. T.M. Peter (1980) to argue that varying compensation frameworks across acquisition laws do not violate Article 14.


Asserted that the action was undertaken in good faith and did not infringe constitutional rights.


Respondent (Bimal Kumar Shah):
Argued that the forcible acquisition without due process violated Article 300A, which guarantees the right to property.


Emphasized that no prior notice, hearing, or compensation was provided.


Relied on Nagpur Improvement Trust v. Vithal Rao (1973), which held that acquisition must strictly adhere to statutory and constitutional safeguards.


Contended that the Corporation’s unilateral alteration of records was illegal, arbitrary, and mala fide.



⚖️ 
Judgment
The Supreme Court dismissed the appeal and upheld the High Court’s decision, declaring that the Corporation’s acquisition was illegal, arbitrary, and unconstitutional.
The Court held that:
Section 352 does not empower the Municipal Commissioner to forcibly acquire property; the procedure under Section 537, requiring State Government approval, must be followed.


The unauthorised change in ownership records violated the constitutional mandate under Article 300A.


Property rights, though no longer fundamental, remain protected constitutional rights, and deprivation without lawful procedure is impermissible.


The Court imposed a cost of ₹5,00,000 on the Corporation for its illegal exercise of power.



🧠 
Court’s Reasoning
🔹 1. Scope of Section 352:
Section 352 allows land acquisition only for specified purposes, not forcible occupation. Any exercise of acquisition power without statutory authority amounts to usurpation of property.
🔹 2. Violation of Article 300A:
The right to property can be restricted only by authority of law, meaning a legislative procedure backed by procedural fairness. Arbitrary administrative actions cannot qualify.
🔹 3. Role of Section 537:
Section 537 mandates that where voluntary acquisition fails, the Commissioner must apply to the State Government for authorization. The Corporation’s failure to do so rendered the acquisition void.
🔹 4. Substantive Rights under Article 300A:
The Court identified a cluster of procedural rights implicit in Article 300A, which must guide all property-related state actions:
🧾 Right to Notice


🗣️ Right to be Heard


🧑‍⚖️ Right to a Reasoned Decision


🏗️ Duty to Acquire Only for a Public Purpose


💰 Right to Restitution or Fair Compensation


⚖️ Right to an Efficient and Expeditious Process


📜 Right to Conclusion — finality of proceedings


🔹 5. Accountability of Public Authorities:
The Court emphasized that public bodies are trustees of public power and cannot appropriate private property arbitrarily under the guise of “public purpose.” The doctrine of constitutional morality requires transparency, fairness, and lawful conduct in every administrative action.

🧾 
Final Holding
The appeal by KMC was dismissed.


The respondent’s ownership was restored, and KMC was directed to pay ₹5,00,000 as costs.


The Court reaffirmed that Article 300A guarantees more than a procedural right—it embodies a substantive right to lawful, fair, and reasoned deprivation.



🔗 
Referred / Related Cases
1️⃣ Nagpur Improvement Trust v. Vithal Rao (1973) 1 SCC 500 – Acquisition without fair procedure violates constitutional equality.
2️⃣ State of Kerala v. T.M. Peter (1980) 3 SCC 554 – Different compensation schemes under various statutes do not necessarily violate Article 14.
3️⃣ K.T. Plantation Pvt. Ltd. v. State of Karnataka (2011) 9 SCC 1 – Article 300A safeguards property as a constitutional right subject to due process.
4️⃣ State of U.P. v. Manohar (2005) 2 SCC 126 – Arbitrary deprivation of property by state officials is unconstitutional.
5️⃣ Hindustan Petroleum Corp. Ltd. v. Darius Shapur Chenai (2005) 7 SCC 627 – Strict compliance with acquisition procedure is mandatory.

💡 
Significance
This judgment fortifies the constitutional right to property under Article 300A, clarifying that even municipal or local authorities are bound by due process. It reinforces the judiciary’s role in curbing administrative arbitrariness and expands the jurisprudence on procedural fairness in property acquisition.
⚖️ “Public purpose cannot justify private injustice — no authority can bypass the due process of law under the guise of urgency.” — Supreme Court of India

📘 CS-24-38 | Lalu Yadav v. State of Uttar Pradesh & Ors. (2024)
Citation: 2024 INSC 782 (18 September 2024)
Bench: Justice C.T. Ravikumar and Justice Rajesh Bindal

⚖️ Background
This case examines whether a long-term consensual relationship followed by an unfulfilled promise of marriage can attract criminal liability under Sections 376 (rape) and 313 (causing miscarriage without consent) of the Indian Penal Code (IPC). It also considers the scope of the High Court’s powers under Article 226 of the Constitution and Section 482 of the Code of Criminal Procedure (CrPC) to quash criminal proceedings that appear to be an abuse of process.
The complainant alleged that the appellant, Lalu Yadav, engaged in a physical relationship with her over several years, assuring marriage, and later pressured her to terminate her pregnancies. The FIR was lodged five years after the alleged incidents. The appellant sought quashing of the FIR, arguing that the relationship was consensual, mutually sustained, and known to both families.

🧩 
Key Issues
1️⃣ Whether a prolonged consensual relationship, based on a promise of marriage that was later unfulfilled, can constitute rape under Section 376 IPC.
2️⃣ Whether Section 313 IPC (causing miscarriage without consent) can apply when the complainant’s own statement does not indicate absence of consent.
3️⃣ Whether the High Court erred in refusing to exercise its powers under Article 226 or Section 482 CrPC to quash the FIR, despite the absence of coercion or deception.

📜 
Relevant Provisions
Section 376, IPC – Punishment for rape.


Section 313, IPC – Causing miscarriage without consent.


Article 226, Constitution of India – Power of High Courts to issue writs.


Section 482, CrPC – Inherent powers of the High Court to prevent abuse of process and secure ends of justice.



📂 
Facts of the Case
The complainant alleged that the appellant entered into a sexual relationship with her over several years, promising marriage.


When her family discovered the relationship, the appellant reassured them of his intent to marry but later withdrew his promise.


She further claimed that he compelled her to undergo abortions during the relationship.


The FIR was filed five years after the alleged incidents, following the appellant’s eventual refusal to marry.


The appellant filed a writ petition under Article 226 before the High Court, asserting that the relationship was consensual and that the complaint was retaliatory.


The High Court declined to quash the FIR, prompting the appellant to appeal to the Supreme Court.



⚖️ 
Judgment
The Supreme Court quashed the FIR and all related criminal proceedings. The Court held that the allegations reflected a consensual relationship, not one vitiated by coercion or fraud sufficient to invoke Section 376 IPC. It emphasized that criminal law cannot be used to punish failed relationships or emotional disputes where mutual consent existed throughout.

🧠 
Court’s Reasoning
🔹 1. Absence of Coercion or Deception:
The Court observed that both parties had maintained a voluntary relationship for several years. There was no evidence that the complainant’s consent was obtained through deceit or coercion at the inception of the relationship — a key element under Section 376 IPC.
🔹 2. Delay in Filing FIR:
The five-year delay in lodging the complaint was unexplained and undermined the credibility of the allegations. The Court noted that while delay alone does not nullify a complaint, it weakens the evidentiary foundation when the relationship was openly maintained and consensual.
🔹 3. Section 313 IPC Inapplicable:
The complainant’s statements indicated voluntary medical termination of pregnancy. Since lack of consent is an essential element under Section 313 IPC, the provision could not apply.
🔹 4. Application of Bhajan Lal Principles:
Referring to State of Haryana v. Bhajan Lal (1992 Supp (1) SCC 335), the Court reaffirmed that FIRs should be quashed where allegations are inherently improbable, absurd, or filed to settle personal scores. The allegations in this case fell squarely within those parameters.
🔹 5. Inherent Powers under Section 482 CrPC:
The Court reiterated that inherent jurisdiction must be exercised to prevent abuse of legal process and protect individuals from frivolous criminal prosecution. Where consensual relationships are later reinterpreted as coercive merely due to personal differences, continuation of criminal proceedings constitutes such abuse.

🧾 
Final Holding
The FIR and all consequential proceedings were quashed.


The Court declared that consensual relationships, even when followed by emotional fallout or unfulfilled marriage promises, cannot be criminalized as rape unless deception existed from the very beginning.


The Court reaffirmed that delay, mutual consent, and absence of coercion are critical factors in determining criminal culpability.



🔗 
Important Cases Referred
1️⃣ State of Haryana v. Bhajan Lal (1992) – Enumerated circumstances under which an FIR can be quashed to prevent abuse of process.
2️⃣ Shivashankar alias Shiva v. State of Karnataka (2019) – Held that long-term consensual relationships cannot automatically translate into rape charges upon refusal of marriage.
3️⃣ XXXX v. State of Madhya Pradesh (2024) – Clarified that sustained mutual consent negates the elements of rape under Section 376 IPC.
4️⃣ Pramod Suryabhan Pawar v. State of Maharashtra (2019) – Explained that a false promise of marriage amounts to rape only if deceit exists at the inception.
5️⃣ Deepak Gulati v. State of Haryana (2013) – Distinguished between breach of promise and false promise made to manipulate consent.

💡 
Significance
This ruling strengthens jurisprudence on the misuse of Section 376 IPC in romantic or intimate disputes, emphasizing that criminal law must not intrude into consensual private relationships. It reinforces judicial discipline under Section 482 CrPC, ensuring that criminal proceedings serve justice rather than vengeance.
⚖️ “Consent freely given in a relationship of mutual affection cannot be retrospectively converted into coercion merely due to emotional rupture.” — Supreme Court of India


CS-24-39 | Legal Consequences Arising from the Policies and Practices of Israel in the Occupied Palestinian Territory, Including East Jerusalem (2024)

⚖️ Bench
International Court of Justice (ICJ) — Advisory Opinion, delivered on 19 July 2024

📜 Relevant Provisions
Article 96, UN Charter – Power of the General Assembly to request advisory opinions from the ICJ.


Hague Regulations, 1907 and Fourth Geneva Convention, 1949 – Rules on occupation and protection of civilians.


Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination (CERD) – Prohibition of discriminatory practices.


Right to Self-Determination (Jus Cogens) – Fundamental, non-derogable principle under international law.


Jus ad Bellum – Prohibition on acquisition of territory by force.



🏛️ Background
The United Nations General Assembly (December 2022) requested an advisory opinion from the ICJ on the legal consequences of Israel’s policies and practices in the Occupied Palestinian Territory (OPT), including East Jerusalem.
The request covered several areas:
Israel’s occupation, settlement construction, and annexation activities;


Discriminatory laws and movement restrictions;


Land confiscation and home demolitions;


Failure to protect Palestinian civilians from settler violence.


Israel filed a written statement but did not participate in oral hearings, while multiple States and international organizations submitted interventions.

❓ Key Issues
Whether Israel’s continued presence in the Occupied Palestinian Territory is lawful under international law.


Whether settlement expansion, annexation, and discriminatory measures violate international humanitarian and human rights law.


What legal consequences arise for Israel, other States, and international organizations, including obligations of cessation, non-recognition, non-assistance, and reparation.



⚖️ Court’s Analysis
The Court reaffirmed that the Occupied Palestinian Territory remains under belligerent occupation, and Israel’s activities — including settlements, annexation, land confiscation, and movement restrictions — violate international humanitarian law, human rights law, and the Palestinian people’s right to self-determination.


Settlements and annexation constitute de facto sovereignty and permanent demographic alteration, which are incompatible with the temporary nature of occupation.


Israel’s presence has thus become unlawful, and it must withdraw completely and cease all activities that perpetuate the occupation.


All States and international organizations have erga omnes obligations not to recognize or aid in maintaining this unlawful situation.


The Court emphasized the duty of the UN to take effective measures to ensure compliance and restoration of Palestinian rights.



🧾 Judgment / Findings
Israel’s continued occupation of the OPT is unlawful under international law.


Israel must:


End its presence immediately,


Cease all settlement activity,


Evacuate settlers, and


Provide reparations for the harm caused to Palestinians.


All States must:


Not recognize or assist the unlawful situation,


Refrain from any acts implying legitimization of Israel’s control, and


Cooperate to ensure compliance with international obligations.


The United Nations should take appropriate institutional measures to bring the unlawful situation to an end.



💡 Significance
Reaffirms that self-determination is a jus cogens norm, violation of which entails universal legal responsibility.


Clarifies the duties of third States — including India — in cases of prolonged occupation and annexation.


Establishes a clear distinction between lawful occupation and unlawful annexation under international law.


Strengthens the ICJ’s evolving jurisprudence on State responsibility, human rights, and non-recognition obligations.



CS-24-40 | Manish Sisodia v. Directorate of Enforcement (2024 INSC 595)

⚖️ 
Bench
Justice B.R. Gavai and Justice K.V. Viswanathan

📜 
Background
This case arises from allegations of corruption and money laundering in relation to the Delhi Excise Policy 2021–22. The appellant, Manish Sisodia, then Deputy Chief Minister of Delhi, was accused of manipulating the excise policy to extend undue benefits to private entities in exchange for kickbacks.
Following a letter by the Lieutenant Governor of Delhi, the Ministry of Home Affairs initiated an inquiry, leading to a CBI FIR and a parallel Enforcement Directorate (ED) case under the Prevention of Money Laundering Act, 2002 (PMLA).
Sisodia was arrested first by the CBI (February 2023) and later by the ED (March 2023). The CBI filed a charge sheet under Sections 7, 7A, 8, and 12 of the Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988 read with Sections 420, 201, and 120B of the Indian Penal Code, 1860. The ED followed with a complaint under Section 3 of the PMLA.
After two rounds of bail rejections by the Delhi High Court, Sisodia appealed to the Supreme Court, contending that continued incarceration violated his fundamental right to liberty under Article 21.

⚖️ 
Relevant Provisions
Article 21, Constitution of India – Right to life and personal liberty.


Section 439, Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 – Power of High Court to grant bail.


Sections 7, 7A, 8, 12, Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988.


Sections 420, 201, 120B, Indian Penal Code, 1860.


Sections 3 and 45, Prevention of Money Laundering Act, 2002.



🧩 
Key Issue
Whether the right to bail can be read into Section 45 of the PMLA when the accused has spent a long period in custody and there is a significant delay in trial proceedings.

⚖️ 
Arguments
Appellant (Sisodia):
The trial involved 493 witnesses and more than one lakh pages of documents, making early conclusion impossible.


Continued incarceration without commencement of trial violated Article 21 and amounted to punishment without conviction.


The investigation had concluded, and most evidence was documentary, minimizing any risk of tampering.


The twin conditions of Section 45 PMLA should be relaxed in cases of prolonged custody to protect constitutional liberty.


Respondent (Enforcement Directorate):
Sisodia was a highly influential public official capable of influencing witnesses and obstructing justice.


The delay in trial was partly caused by the defence filing multiple applications.


Bail should not be granted unless the twin conditions under Section 45 were satisfied.



⚖️ 
Judgment
The Supreme Court allowed the appeal, quashing the Delhi High Court’s order and granting bail to Manish Sisodia in both CBI and ED cases.
The Court observed that:
There was “not even a remotest possibility” of the trial being concluded soon given the massive volume of evidence and 495 witnesses.


To keep the appellant in custody indefinitely “would result in a grave violation of the right to personal liberty under Article 21.”


The right to bail must be read into Section 45 of the PMLA when prolonged incarceration and delay in trial are not attributable to the accused.


The appellant had “deep roots in society” and was not a flight risk. Conditions could be imposed to prevent interference with the investigation.


The Court reiterated that “bail is the rule and jail is the exception”, cautioning lower courts against treating pre-trial detention as punitive.



⚖️ 
Ratio Decidendi
When there is inordinate delay in trial and the accused has spent substantial time in custody, the constitutional guarantee of personal liberty under Article 21 overrides the statutory rigour of Section 45 PMLA. The Court emphasized that prolonged detention without trial amounts to punishment before conviction, which is impermissible.

📚 
Important Precedents Referred
Ramkripal Meena v. Directorate of Enforcement (2024) – Relaxed Section 45 twin conditions due to prolonged custody and delayed trial.


Vijay Madanlal Choudhary v. Union of India (2022) – Upheld Section 45 PMLA but recognized Article 21 safeguards.


Satender Kumar Antil v. CBI (2022) – Affirmed that the right to speedy trial is part of Article 21.


Gudikanti Narasimhulu v. Public Prosecutor (1978) – Bail should not be withheld as punishment.


Prabir Purkayastha v. State (NCT of Delhi) (2024) – Reiterated that life and liberty are sacrosanct rights under Article 21.



🧭 
Conclusion
The Supreme Court granted regular bail to Manish Sisodia, setting a precedent that constitutional liberty under Article 21 must guide the interpretation of special statutes like PMLA, particularly where the trial is unreasonably delayed.
The Court’s decision reaffirmed that detention cannot substitute for punishment and underscored that procedural law must serve justice, not obstruct it.